lee grant's boss says the veteran salesman was fired because of his unseemly habit of wearing loud and ugly sport coats. grant, 62, had filed a discrimination suit to prove he was forced out because of his age
grant said before he lost his job at darby buick in sarasota in may 1985, the dealership was undergoing a ``new image'' campaign and he was told to start wearing sport coats on the used car lot for a more professional look
the 30-year sales veteran promptly went shopping for two jackets he describes as a pale pink and a rainbow plaid. he said the latter has every color in it and goes well with his gray slacks or green or red or blue
i saw nothing wrong with them,'' grant said in a sworn statement in u.s. district court in tampa. at 6-foot-8, he said, he has to buy his clothes at specialty shops that fit tall men. and he wanted coats to go with his different trousers
so that's what i bought, you know, because i had gray pants, blue pants, green pants, every kind. so you had to have something to go with all of them.''
but his boss, c. conrad darby iii, said that neither jacket went well with the image he was trying to create for his dealership
rather than promote an image of professionalism, grant's selections took the opposite direction,'' an attorney for darby buick said in court documents. ``one jacket was multi-colored ... and the other was a loud fuchsia color.''
in the lawsuit, wryly dubbed ``the dress of a salesman'' in courthouse corridors, grant claims the dress code and other charges against him, including catnapping and snacking in the office, are pretexts to hide the real problem _ age bias
grant, the oldest salesman and the dealership's top in used car sales in 1984, was replaced by a less experienced person in his 20s, was never reprimanded and had an excellent job performance record, said grant's attorney, nancy k. donnellan
darby's attorney, william e. sizemore, acknowledged that grant was among the best in the sales force. as a result, sizemore said, there was no motive to fire grant for age discrimination, only for his poor behavior
the case is expected to go to trial this month
a wallaroo apparently blinded by the milk of human kindness underwent cataract surgery by two doctors who volunteered their services and usually treat people
in saturday's three-hour operation, dr. raymond weinstein, a family practitioner, and dr. gene zdenek, an ophthalmologist, removed a marble-sized cataract from the eye of the animal, a stocky kangaroo. the doctors tentatively declared the operation a success
weinstein said an improper diet probably blinded the animal, named menehuni, who apparently had been blind most of its seven to 11 years
milk sugars collect in the eyes of wallaroos and cause cataracts because the animals cannot break them down, weinstein said
this poor guy's condition illustrates the reason why most people shouldn't have exotic animals,'' zdenek said. ``the people probably had no idea they were blinding their pet.''
state authorities took menehuni from its owners and gave him to the wildlife way station in the angeles national forest, a nonprofit group that cares for exotic and wild animals that are sick or abandoned
the surgery was performed for free at the station with the help of resident veterinarian silvio santinelli
weinstein said it was the first time he had to worry about ``moving a patient's tail out of the way.''
dorothy was coming downstairs for some tea when she heard five shots in the middle of the night. right away she thought of police sgt. edward byrne, sitting alone in a patrol car a block away, guarding the home of a threatened witness
i said, `oh my god, he's in trouble,''' she recalled
now, sitting in her tidy living room in the south jamaica section of queens, dorothy _ a middle-age woman afraid to give her last name _ mourns byrne, 22, a rookie who police believe was slain on the orders of a jailed drug kingpin
and she mourns for her neighborhood of small wood-frame houses that once must have seemed promising to working-class people looking for a slice of prosperity
it doesn't anymore
south jamaica has been overwhelmed by drugs, especially crack, in an epidemic that reached a peak of violence in the murder of byrne, who was guarding the home of a man who had complained about drug dealers
although police have taken the neighborhood by storm in efforts to ferret out byrne's killers and drive away the drug merchants, residents remain cynical and scared
south jamaica, solidly black and poor, has been a troubled neighborhood for a long time. it shows in peeling paint, sagging porches, abandoned storefronts
but things have taken a turn for the worse in the past few years and police, clergy and residents blame crack and the people who sell it
they have taken over, completely taken over,'' said city councilman archie spigner, who represents south jamaica. ``everywhere i go, there are complaints. every community meeting i attend, the inevitable complaint is narcotics.''
the users commit other crimes to support their habits. children, seeing drug dealers in flashy clothes and fancy cars, are drawn to the drug life. lawbreakers are drawn to the neighborhood. and dealers engage in turf wars that endanger all around them
you hear gunshots here and you hear gunshots there,'' said richard barnes, who lost a new television set and a videocassette recorder in a burglary he blames on drug addicts. ``if i had the money, i'd move.''
when crack first spread through new york city several years ago, experts said it was sold by small-time entrepreneurs who would buy an ounce of cocaine and process it into a flaky, smokable drug
but now officials say a new hierarchy of violent, well-armed drug kingpins is taking over the crack trade in queens
it starts in a very low-key way,'' said william hopkins, who supervises the street research unit of the state division of substance abuse services. an entrepreneur begins selling drugs in a neighborhood and builds up a reputation. buyers begin driving into the neighborhood
after a while, the dealer's success comes to the attention of a nearby drug gang. they make him an offer that he can't refuse, ``work for us or get killed.''
once that organized group comes in there, you're dealing with guns and it's not easy to get rid of,'' hopkins said
what makes a neighborhood susceptible to drug infestation, beyond having at least some drug users?
james beshers, a demographer at queens college, believes that an influx of different ethnic groups into a neighborhood can create a breakdown in the social structure that is conducive to illegal activity
you get a loss of communication,'' beshers said. he noted that south jamaica has seen an influx of asian and west indian immigrants who can't necessarily communicate well with each other or with the established residents, mostly blacks who grew up in new york or in the south
for archie spigner, the reason for the infestation in south jamaica is more prosaic: ``the police just allowed it to exist. they just accepted it, and it became entrenched, it became institutionalized.''
the police department, shocked by byrne's murder, has set out to end such criticism. police commissioner benjamin ward announced plans last week for a new, 118-member tactical narcotics team whose mission is to stamp out drug dealing in southeast queens
and an intense investigation has already led to the indictment of four men on charges of murdering the young cop
but skepticism runs high in south jamaica, where some residents are bitter that it took the murder of a police officer to bring attention to their plight
what about the kids being killed in the drug wars?'' asked a man who walked down a street a block from the murder site and refused to give his name. ``that's what people ought to be crying about. i know about 10 cases of young kids getting killed in the neighborhood, and nobody ever did anything about that.''
porno star john holmes, who boasted of 14,000 sexual conquests, on and off screen, during a career in x-rated films and peep shows that spanned two decades, died saturday at age 43
holmes, the leading male sex film star of the 1970s and early 1980s, died at the veterans administration medical center, said adult-film producer william amerson, a longtime friend and business associate
the los angeles times earlier this month quoted unidentified sources as saying holmes was gravely ill with aids. amerson said the cause of death was not immediately known
holmes, best known for his portrayal of the character johnny wadd, a detective, made thousands of peep shows and sexually explicit films, including ``liquid lips,'' ``blonde fire,'' ``tell them johnny wadd is here'' and ``exhausted.''
he once admitted that he had a $1,000-a-day cocaine habit
two weeks ago detectives again questioned holmes at his hospital bedside about the unsolved 1981 slayings of four people in a house in laurel canyon
holmes was acquitted of the slayings in 1982 but had never told authorities what he knew about the crime
romare bearden, a leading american artist whose collages expressed the dignity of black people and southern living, died saturday. he was 75
bearden's work ranged from political cartoons to water colors, sets and costumes for the alvin ailey dance theater, public murals and eventually collages. he was awarded the national medal of arts by president reagan in june
lowery sims, associate curator of 20th century art at the metropolitan museum of art, said bearden's collages ``raised it to such a fine art it's hard to think of any other artist who is so closely associated with that medium.''
bearden was born in charlotte, n.c., and grew up in harlem and pittsburgh. he attended boston university and new york university, majoring in mathematics and planning to become a doctor
he started drawing in college, and cartoons published in the afro american, a weekly, led to a career in art
hugh wolfe frank, chief interpreter at the nuremberg war crimes trials, was found dead thursday. he was 75
frank was a skillful linguist who led the team of interpreters at the trials in west germany of top nazis, including hermann goering and rudolf hess
frank, whose body was found in a fume-filled car, had been suffering from parkinson's disease and was known to be depressed about his worsening health. an inquest was ordered
joseph t. sternaman, the first quarterback of the chicago bears, died thursday at age 88
in the bears' first season, in 1922, sternaman and his brother edward ``dutch'' sternaman, a halfback and co-owner of the fledgling nfl team with bears founder george halas, accounted for 73 of the team's 123 points
at 135 pounds, sternaman also served as a runner, drop-kicker and blocker. he called plays featuring red grange, the ``galloping ghost'' of the university of illinois
murray m. ``buddy'' weiss, former editor of the international herald tribune, died saturday at age 64
the new york native, who worked for the u.s. information agency at the time of his death, was editor of the paris-based newspaper from its creation in 1966 until 1979
in 1946, he joined the new york herald tribune as a copy boy and was managing editor by the time the paper folded in 1966
after leaving the international herald tribune, he served as editor of the advocate in stamford, conn., and managing editor of parade magazine. he left parade in 1983
at usia, he was in charge of the news file distributed to u.s. embassies and diplomatic missions around the world
j.w. jung, founder of one of the nation's biggest mail-order seed companies, died friday at the age of 100
the jung seed co., founded here in 1906, circulates between 2 million and 3 million seed catalogs a year and also operates a garden center in randolph
jung traced his interest in gardening and seeds to his boyhood, when his mother taught him to save seeds from the vegetable garden for planting. he soon was going from farm to farm selling extra seeds
steno, an italian director of film comedies, died of a stroke sunday
born stefano vanzina in 1917, he began his career as a screenwriter in 1945 and soon after began directing. some, such as ``guardie e ladri'' (guards and thieves), starred one of italy's best-loved comics, toto. poll showing simon with strong lead in illinois; picks up 8th graf pvs bgng, `simon and'</note>
with signs pointing to another republican primary victory by george bush in illinois, the vice president came under renewed criticism sunday from gop rival bob dole and from democrats jesse jackson and albert gore jr
two polls published in monday's editions of two newspapers gave contradictory indications of how the democratic voters were expected to cast ballots in tuesday's primary
the poll in the chicago tribune showed jackson moving into the lead, favored by 32 percent of the democrats, illinois sen. paul simon by 29 percent and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis by 20 percent
five hundred likely democratic primary voters were contacted thursday and friday and the survey had a margin of error of 5 percent, meaning the numbers could be off that much up or down
however, a poll for the washington post and abc news showed simon holding a strong lead with 42 percent, jackson 33 percent, dukakis 14 percent, sen. gore of tennessee 4 percent, rep. richard gephardt of missouri 3 percent and others and undecided, 4 percent. that poll was based on telephone interviews friday night and saturday with 287 democratic voters who were likely to cast ballots. the margin of error was 6 percent
simon, dependent on a home-state victory to remain in the race, said he had overcome poor showings in polls during other campaigns
if i get my message across to the people of illinois, they're going to vote for me,'' he said
the new chicago tribune poll indicated slippage in simon's support. a survey published in the tribune on sunday said the senator was leading with support from 35 percent of likely democratic voters, while jackson had the backing of 30 percent and dukakis that of 18 percent
simon and dukakis also traded barbs on the question of whether the democratic nomination would be determined by a brokered convention next july in atlanta
the tribune poll on sunday also showed bush with a 34-point lead over dole. the newspaper did not continue surveying republicans
dole, struggling to revive his presidential campaign, insisted he would fight on ``full bore'' after illinois though he said he had no obligation ``to look ridiculous.''
gore, who hopes to demonstrate some northern support in illinois, said he would ``almost certainly'' turn down his party's vice presidential nomination
gore, at a campaign stop later, also blasted bush over the iran-contra affair
the reagan-bush administration violated the law in a brazen way,'' he said, adding: ``we still don't know what george bush's role was.''
interviewed on the cbs show, ``face the nation,'' dole said he received telegram from former president richard nixon who urged him ``hang in there, don't give up, make illinois your finest hour.''
i believe i have some obligation _ not to look ridiculous _ but some obligation to stay in this race,'' said the kansas senator
asked if there was any chance he's drop out after illinois, dole said, ``we're going full bore'' on the wisconsin, which holds its primary on april 5
bush attended a polish-language mass at st. hyacinth church on the city's northwest side and described his trip to poland last year and his meeting with solidarity leader lech walesa
it is the united states of america that must keep alive the hope of the polish people,'' the vice president told a crowd that filled the church and spilled onto the sidewalk outside
after church, bush planned a day of appearances at shopping malls and restaurants, each event described by his staff as a ``photo opportunity only.''
on the possibility of a brokered convention, dukakis said, ``i can't imagine anything worse _ the idea of taking the right of the people to elect their president with their votes and putting it in some backrooms in atlanta.''
simon, predicting no democrat would be able win the nomination on the first ballot at the convention, said dukakis' attitude demonstrated ``a touch of arrogance.'' he described the massachusetts governor as saying, ``you either vote for me or you'll have a brokered convention.''
gore also came to simon's defense and criticized dukakis, saying, ``gov. dukakis' commercial tries to lump him in with back-room politics of a kind paul simon has not been associated with.''
jackson, fresh from a victory in democratic caucuses in south carolina on saturday where he won 54 percent of the vote and picked up 23 delegates, said he hoped by the end of the primary and caucus season in june to have received ``a majority of the popular vote.''
asked about the prospects of running against bush in the general election, jackson said on the nbc show, ``meet the press,'' ``he certainly has a lot of baggage
george bush was supposed to be over the commission on the drug situation, yet drugs are coming into this country at a rate that threatens our national security. ... to that continuous flow of drugs, mrs. reagan says no and george bush says nothing.''
the latest associated press delegate count showed dukakis the democratyic leader with 460 and jackson second with 423. gore was third with 352. a total of 2,082 is needed for the nomination
on the republican side, bush had 705 and dole 165, with 1,139 need for the nomination
gore, who received 18 percent of the south carolina vote and 6 delegates, said he consideed that ``a very good showing.''
i don't know of anyone weho was surprised to see jesse jackson win a big victory in his home state, his native state,'' the tennessee senator said on ``face the nation.''
dole denied he dislikes bush, but said, ``i do believe that he's sort of had a charmed life in politics, he's gotten quite a ways without doing very much. maybe that's a key to success i hadn't thought of.''
the senator renewed his debate challenge to bush and raised again the question of a possible tie between the vice president and panamanian strong man gen. manuel noriega who has been accused of involvement in drug trafficking
i'd like george bush to tell us whether noriega was on his payroll when he was cia director,'' said dole
as for his prospects for a comeback, dole said, ``sooner or later, the voters in one of these states are going to say, wait a minute, we're about to nominate someone who can't win in november.'' after 5th graf to include effect on national delegates.</note>
jesse jackson won easily saturday in his native south carolina's democratic precinct caucuses, giving his already surging campaign a boost just days before the primary in his adopted illinois
just because you're born in the slum doesn't mean the slum's borne in you,'' jackson said in greenville. ``i came home tonight to tell america there is a way out.''
with 93 percent of the state's 1,788 precincts reporting, jackson won 8,114 county convention delegates for 54 percent, followed by uncommitted with 2,853 delegates for 19 percent
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. was in third place with 2,777 delegates for 18 percent
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis trailed far behind with 1,018 county convention delegates for 7 percent, followed by missouri rep. richard gephardt with 307 delegates for 2 percent and illinois sen. paul simon with just 36 delegates
if the results of the caucuses hold up at the state convention in april, jackson would win 23 delegates to the democratic national convention, 15 would be uncommitted and gore would gain 6. in addition another four party officials in the state, who automatically are delegates to the national convention, have said they are uncommitted
the results from south carolina put jackson's overall national delegate tally at 423.55, just behind dukakis, who has 460.5
in south carolina ... i want to win another gold medal,'' jackson said, noting his strong showing in the super tuesday primaries
i hope to walk away with the majority,'' jackson said. ``i should be the favorite son from south carolina.''
gephardt, who was campaigning in michigan, congratulated jackson on his victory, saying ``i thought he would do very well there -it's his home state - and he did.''
gore spokesman fred martin called his candidate's performance ``a strong showing'' and added ``we expect to pick up a majority of the uncommitted.''
democratic party officials expected as many as 20,000 voters would participate in the caucuses in which 44 convention delegates were at stake
during a campaign swing across the state friday, jackson predicted he would emerge as the leader in the muddled race for convention delegates once the votes are tallied in south carolina and illinois, which holds a primary on tuesday
jackson trails dukakis but leads gore in the race for delegates to the democratic national convention
gore has waged an active campaign in the state and a newspaper survey of democratic party chairmen statewide found gore expected to finish second to jackson
in the past, south carolina democrats have had a penchant for going to the caucuses and voting for uncommitted delegates. jackson was the top candidate four years ago but a plurality of the delegates remained uncommitted at the precinct level
this time around, campaign aides for gephardt and simon, were asking their supporters to remain uncommitted and work to become delegates at county conventions later in the month
but gore urged supporters during a stop in charleston friday to stand up for his candidacy and ``don't let anyone talk you into being an uncommitted delegate.'' dukakis aides wanted voters to commit to him
the caucuses are the first stage of a three-stage process to select national convention delegates. voters were to select delegates to the county conventions which in turn selects delegates to the state convention
the delegates are divided proportionally based on a candidates' showing. but only those candidates with 15 percent of the vote at the state convention are entitled to national convention delegates. delegates selected saturday are bound to their candidates through the county and state conventions
jake hill, gore's assistant campaign coordinator, suggested neither gephardt nor simon would be able to round up the 15 percent of votes to allow them to receive any delegates
the campaigns would ask their people to stay uncommitted in the hopes something could be worked out at the county or state conventions to allow them to secure some delegates, he suggested
although the caucuses have been overshadowed by south carolina's republican primary and the parade of gop candidates it attracted, gephardt, gore and jackson all stumped in the state during the past week
gephardt had the endorsements of former govs. dick riley and robert mcnair. he promoted his trade policy this week at a campaign stop at a clearwater textile plant that will be closed next month
but during the stop, gephardt said he hoped to get his campaign back on track by winning the michigan primary march 26
while dukakis and simon both campaigned in the state earlier, neither has returned in recent weeks
a storm packing winds of up to 60 miles per hour capsized scores of small fishing boats, flattened hundreds of mud and straw huts and at least 15 people were feared dead, police said sunday
rescue workers searched the banks of the jamuna river on sunday for survivors of the friday storm in mankiganj district, northwest of dhaka, officials said
we see slim chances that the missing are still surviving,'' said a police official in manikganj, who spoke in a telephone interview on condition of anonymity
he said no bodies had yet been recovered
the storm along the river was slow in being reported because the wind also damaged electrical and telephone wires in the region
more than 300 mud and straw huts were flattened, and trees and crops damaged, officials said. more than 50 fishing boats were believed capsized or sunk
iraq said sunday its warplanes attacked a supertanker off the iranian coast, while its ground forces beat back an iranian offensive in a pre-dawn battle in the central sector of the war front
the official iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, reported more than 1,000 iranians were killed in the 3{-hour battle which began at 1 a.m
ina said two iranian brigades, backed by tanks and artillery, were involved in the thrust
infantry units of iraq's 2nd army corps repulsed the thrust, exterminating the bulk of the force. more than 1,000 iranians were killed and the others were forced to retreat,'' the agency quoted an unnamed spokesman as saying
there was no immediate word from iran on the reported battle
iraq did not say where exactly the battle took place, but judging from the size of the force, the attack did not appear to signal the beginning of iran's long-awaited major offensive
the large-scale attack is expected to be launched in the southern sector of the 730-mile front around basra, iraq's second-largest city and its only outlet to the persian gulf
iran's last thrust in january 1987, brought iranian troops to within six miles of basra. but western military analysts say iran has had difficulties mobilizing forces needed for a new attack
in a separate dispatch, ina quoted a military spokesman as saying iraqi planes ``dealt an accurate and effective blow to a very large maritime target,'' a reference to a supertanker, off the iranian coast during the night
the report could not be immediately confirmed
ellison onizuka and michael smith both were military officers. they trained together for two years to be astronauts. and they died together when the space shuttle challenger blew up above the florida coast
though both were servicemen, the government contributed to a money award for air force lt. col. onizuka's relatives but went to court to avoid paying damages in navy cmdr. smith's case
dick scobee, judith resnik and ronald mcnair were civilian nasa astronauts who died in the jan. 28, 1986, explosion. the government contributed to a settlement with scobee's dependents, but refused to contribute to settlements reached with the resnik and mcnair families by rocket maker morton thiokol
i'm hoping some of this inequity will lead to legislation to address the problems of the government's negligence,'' says lawyer michael d. oldak, resnik's ex-husband
why did the government settle with some astronaut families and not with others?
one crucial difference: the families of resnik, smith, and mcnair hired lawyers to negotiate for them. their lawyers objected to justice department positions in the case, and these three families are not likely to see any money from the government
the government did settle _ along with thiokol _ with the four families who hired no lawyers: the scobees, the onizukas and the survivors of the two non-government crew members, teacher christa mcauliffe and hughes aircraft engineer gregory jarvis
these four spouses and six children shared in cash and annuities that cost $7,735,000. the government paid 40 percent; thiokol, 60 percent
they had relied on informal advice from the law partner of mcauliffe's husband, steven, and they talked only with the government, never directly with the company
another difference is that once those four cases were settled dec. 29, 1986, justice department lawyers took an our-way-or-no-way approach to negotiating with the other families
the government sought to apply the same formula for financial benefits to each family. at the same time, it tried to negotiate a legal minefield bounded by two key supreme court decisions
in one decision, the high court gave the government immunity from being sued for damages for its military and civilian employees who are killed on the job. justice department lawyers did not want to see that doctrine weakened
in the other decision, the supreme court said a contractor who pays damages for the death of a federal worker can try to get some of that money back from the government, if federal employees shared in the blame
the government did not want to be dragged into court by thiokol for a replay of the errors by government officials who spurned the protests of company engineers that it was too cold to launch challenger
the two decisions left the government with direct liability for two challenger astronauts and only indirect liability for the five federal workers aboard. the justice department's solution: settle only when the company also was a party
the split between the families had its roots in the government's financial benefit formula, based on the number and age of dependents and their needs and goals
justice spokeswoman amy brown said ``generous offers based on the same formula'' were made to all seven families. but the families with lawyers rejected them
the formula left out an element common to most court-awarded damages _ a calculation of lost wages
legal experts say this benefited the mcauliffe family, because the earning potential of public school teacher christa mcauliffe was dwarfed by that of her fellow crew members, who were engineers and physicists, all but one with advanced degrees
one lawyer involved in the negotiations said steven mcauliffe helped devise the formula and pressed other families to accept it because the government wanted a package settlement
a single settlement covering military, civilian federal and non-government crew members would ease the government's legal problem of having direct liability for some and indirect liability for others, this source said
but the benefit formula did not offer enough money to satisfy michael oldak, lawyer for resnik's divorced father, marvin, and her niece and nephew. a 36-year-old, ph.d. engineer, resnik was the only astronaut with neither spouse nor children
oldak said the formula only provided several hundred thousand dollars for the resniks _ between a quarter and a half of what the government and company were offering the other families
after rejecting two government-company offers, oldak went to thiokol
the company was agreeable to a joint government-company settlement with the resniks for an amount roughly equal to that of jarvis' widow, marcia. hers was the lowest of the four settlements because the jarvises had no children
thiokol would even make up the difference between this figure and the government-company offer that oldak had rejected
checking with marcia jarvis and other relatives, oldak found none who objected to bending the formula this much
but justice officials heard differently. ``it's not accurate that it would not offend other families,'' said justice's brown. ``one might have said ok. two might have, but all of them would not subscribe to that. concern was voiced that an offer might not be in line with the formula used for the others, and we couldn't do that.''
last july, thiokol lawyer john w. adler wrote the government, ``i don't believe that the department's position with respect to the resnik claim has been fair either to the resnik claimants or to morton thiokol.''
ulimately, thiokol settled alone with the resniks; the astronaut's father said it came to $2 million to $3.5 million
thiokol also settled with mcnair's widow and two infants. their lawyer, ronald krist of houston, says he would not let the family accept a joint government-company offer as low that accepted by the other families
he offered to settle separately with the government for whatever it calculated its share was, and he would take on thiokol independently. but the government refused
justice's brown explained, ``we couldn't settle on behalf of the government alone, because there was no direct government liability. our settlement offers were all on behalf of both the government and the company.''
but the joint settlements left the question of liability too murky for smith's widow, jane. ``she didn't feel justice was being served,'' her lawyer, william f. maready said. ``she feels now that the people whose negligence caused the accident should be accountable for their actions.''
she sued thiokol, the government and lawrence mulloy, the nasa engineer responsible for the booster rocket that was blamed for the accident
but last year, the supreme court expanded its 35-year-old doctrine that military survivors may not sue the government. it extended the government's immunity to a case like the challenger disaster, where a military pilot was killed while supervised by federal civilian employees
government lawyers appeared in court and got both the government and mulloy dismissed as defendants
maready has filed notice he intends to appeal
that ruling says, in effect, that a military person is a second class citizen, that no matter how negligent our government was in this situation that the people in the agencies involved aren't accountable,'' maready said. ``it's a dangerous thing for the space program to be run by people who aren't fully accountable.'' spending</head>
the highly touted budget summit agreement, long since enacted into law, definitively settled the question of how much money the federal government should spend this year. right?
wrong
congressional leaders are girding for a fight over whether spending in fiscal year 1988, which is nearly half over, needs to be increased
whether lawmakers adhere to the summit pact and only provide extra money for what the agreement called ``dire emergencies'' rests on whether they succumb to the urge to spend more _ an urging fueled by the fact that this is an election year
in an era of $1 trillion federal budgets, requests for an additional several billion dollars for unforeseen needs are made by the white house and approved by congress virtually every year. they are called supplemental spending bills
but the budget pact concluded by president reagan and congressional leaders forbade supplementals ``except in the case of dire emergency.'' the term was left undefined
lawmakers are already beginning to submit new spending proposals said to be for dire emergencies. one, with 37 co-sponsors, would provide $105 million to the financially strapped coast guard. another, with 20 co-sponsors, would add $263 million in spending for the homeless
my experience around here is it's sort of like a pent-up lake and the dam could break very easily,'' sen. pete v. domenici of new mexico, senior republican on the budget committee and one of the negotiators at last fall's budget summit, says of the congressional proclivity for spending money
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said last week that he interprets dire emergencies to include crises such as natural disasters or military operations
aside from that kind of thing, it's not our expectation, nor our intention'' to approve other kinds of new spending, wright said
indeed, many lawmakers seem to believe that in this election year it could be bad politics to openly preach more spending because of the effect on the deficit
there is another reason for democrats to be leery of a supplemental spending bill. many of them believe it could become a way for aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels to be restored
the administration will ultimately use the supplemental for contra aid,'' predicts rep. vic fazio, d-calif
despite those incentives, some are pessimistic that lawmakers seeking new spending will be thwarted
they'll be caving, and it's unfortunate,'' said rep. delbert latta of ohio, ranking republican on the house budget committee and another summit participant. ``it seems like per usual, everybody's got their program they're particularly interested in that's just not getting enough money.''
lawmakers will be watching closely this week, when the administration says it will submit a supplemental spending bill of its own
the package is expected by congressional aides to be worth between $1 billion and $2 billion, but administration officials say it will produce no red ink. instead, they say the spending for veterans, black lung benefits, the judicial branch, coast guard, prisons and other programs will be offset by cuts in other unspecified areas
if legislators believe that some of the spending in reagan's request is not truly for emergencies, some lawmakers might be encouraged to press for money for programs they favor
under any circumstances, some members of congress might try to attach their requests for new spending to the reagan proposal. such requests, once submitted, might be hard for other lawmakers to resist, especially with elections coming in a few months
for example, the coast guard, because it is low on money, has already announced plans to curtail more than half of its drug enforcement patrols and to close several facilities. members could be hard-pressed to vote against restoring such cuts
even if such efforts lose, lawmakers lose nothing by introducing them and showing their constituents that at least they tried
this is how they start brewing the stew,'' said one congressional aide, who asked not to be identified, about how extra spending gets generated. breathing</head>
as many as 5,000 machines designed to monitor babies at risk of sudden infant death syndrome have faulty alarms that could leave infants vulnerable to death or injury, warns the company that makes them
the devices, manufactured by aequitron medical inc., are designed to sound an alarm if an infant suddenly stops breathing or has an abnormal heart rate. but the machines have a ``higher than acceptable failure rate,'' the company's president, george a. jackson, said last week
the company issued a safety alert, warning dealers about the defect in its new model, no. 9200, which has been shipped to homes and hospitals nationwide since last july. the alert does not affect about 40,000 earlier models
jackson said that no injuries or deaths have been reported, but that the company learned within the last two or three weeks that the alarm had failed in some instances
the device primarily is used in homes to monitor children believed to be at high risk for sids. the mysterious malady is the seventh leading killer of younger americans, according to the national centers for disease control
in some cases, the infants suffer from apnea, a tendency to stop breathing while asleep, jackson said. if the alarm sounds in time, an adult often can awaken the child and restart his or her breathing
jackson said the company is notifying its dealers about the problem by registered letter. the dealers will alert individual customers, who lease the machines for home use
federal prosecutors say they have dropped a fraud count against a former insurance agent who lost all memory of his alleged crime after suffering a heart attack
robert s. jones, 52, had been charged with pocketing $76,386 by filing a false insurance policy claim. federal prosecutors dismissed the charge friday, basing their decision on medical opinion that jones is unable to proceed in court
prosecutors said jones filled out a bogus life insurance form on dec. 14, 1983, backdated it and invented a fake beneficiary to receive the money from his former employer, peoples life insurance co
assistant u.s. attorney r. lynette ranson said jones scanned newspapers for stories on violent or accidental deaths and used those victims' names in the fraudulent policies
she said jones had used the scheme more than once but said prosecutors agreed to press only one count in exchange for a guilty plea
but jones' deteriorating health prevented him from ever making a plea, ranson said
we thought ... that he was playing games, and that's why we held off for a long time,'' ranson said. ``but he really is in bad shape.''
jones was disabled since november 1986, when he suffered a cardiac arrest that included ``one episode of sudden death,'' according to dr. m.i. dababnah
the seizure came three months after jones was charged. it apparently caused him to lose his memory, dababnah said in reports to federal court
that diagnosis was supported by dr. thomas e. andrews, a clinical psychologist for the west virginia disability determination service
he has virtually no memory for significant events within the last five years,'' andrews advised the court. head</head>
a man who said his hearing was damaged when a lufthansa airline attendant spilled hot drinks over his head has won nearly $40,000 in damages, a newspaper reported sunday
the plaintiff, a bahraini lawyer identified as abdul-wahab ahmed bin harmas, had filed the suit against the west german airline in bahrain's high civil court
the lawsuit alleged negligence and said the flight attendant accidentally spilled four pots of hot coffee and tea over his head, according to the english-language gulf daily news
the newspaper said the court awarded him 15,000 dinars, or $39,750, which was one-tenth the amount sought
the paper said the accident occurred during a flight from frankfurt to bahrain, when the plane hit severe turbulence. it gave no precise dates
the man's injuries led to three months' treatment in bahrain, england and germany, the newspaper said
the court ruled that it was the airline's responsibility to ensure the safety of passengers, the paper said. lufthansa officials in bahrain have refused to comment on the case
president hussain muhammad ershad's party increased its already wide margin in parliament by picking up two more seats in weekend repolling, the election commission announced sunday
voting was held saturday in nine districts where violence during the main election march 3 had forced it to be called off. at least 13 people were killed and 300 others injured in clashes march 3, and two more people died in bomb blasts in dhaka during repolling saturday, police said
the country's major opposition parties, which have been waging a campaign since november to oust ershad, boycotted the parliament balloting. they contend that fair elections cannot be held until ershad resigns and have denounced the latest vote as fraudulent
ershad's jatiya party had 249 seats in the 330-member house, according to the latest results. the election commission said the combined opposition party, a coalition of scores of small groups, won 18 seats. two minor parties won two seats each, and independents won 25 seats
the results in three districts have not yet been announced. in one district, where a candidate was killed, voting has been scheduled for april 7
another 30 seats in parliament are reserved for women, who are chosen later
the major opposition parties contend that less than 1 percent of the nation's 48 million registered voters cast ballots in the parliament elections. but government officials say the turnout appeared to be more than 50 percent
ershad scheduled the elections after dissolving parliament 3{ years before its five-year term was set to expire in an effort to appease his foes. the former army general took power in a 1982 bloodless coup and was elected president in a 1986 election
major opposition parties contended that vote was fraudulent
