charles e. ``buddy'' roemer iii, a brash self-styled reformer who unseated a political legend to take office monday as governor, says he faces ``a difficult and interesting job'' in trying to solve louisiana's problems
i think i'm just a representative of the people in this. i think it's a make-or-break situation for the kinds of things we want,'' roemer, 44, said in a recent interview
as gov. edwin edwards leaves office, the state faces the immediate problems of a four-year, $1.2 billion budget deficit and a cash shortage that threatens to shut down state government
fiscal analysts have warned that the state faces as much as a $1 billion shortfall for the 1988-89 fiscal year
the state's unemployment rate hit 12 percent in january, one of the highest in the nation, due primarily to the long-running downturn in the oil and gas industry
at the same time, louisiana's education systems are under challenge as second-rate, business interests are demanding a major overhaul of the state's tax system in order to attract new industry, and environmental groups are calling for tougher regulations to protect the air and water
roemer, who plans major reforms in those areas and others such as in campaign finance practices, said the challenge is unlike that facing any other louisiana governor
we need a combination in the next four years of a crisis manager and a long-term planner,'' he said. ``it's rare that you combine the two. that's what i'm going to have to do as governor
but i've got to do both to get us out of debt and build _ education development, economic development, better environment. it's going to be a difficult and interesting job.''
to get started, the democratic former congressman is planning a low-budget inauguration minus the traditional parade and inaugural night ball. according to his transition office, only $48,000 will be spent on the entire event, less than the $60,000 gov. dave treen spent on the stage used for his swearing-in ceremony in 1980
roemer, who campaigned on the need for a ``revolution'' to turn around the state's declining fortunes, said the first year of his administration will be dedicated to reversing the financial problems and creating a new image for louisiana, often associated with scandal
confidence, attitude and legislative programs _ and then we will slowly fund them over the next four years,'' he said. ``this plan won't be magic, it won't be instant. we've had to build from the ground up. but i'm very pleased with the progress we've made.''
edwards, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last administration defending himself successfully against federal racketeering charges. as solutions for the state's budget problems, he proposed a statewide lottery and casino gambling in new orleans. roemer is opposed to both
roemer said he was happy that edwards was willing to help during the transition between the oct. 24 election and monday's inauguration
at roemer's request edwards appointed brian kendrick, a baton rouge department store executive, as commissioner of administration
edwards also approved about $36 million in budget cuts requested by roemer, but shielded the giant department of health and human resources from the fiscal ax
roemer is considering splitting the agency into two departments as part of a reorganization program to be studied by a special legislative session later this month. short-term budget reductions also will be on the agenda
kendrick has spearheaded efforts to minimize the cash-flow problem by pushing back more than $480 million in expenditures until the new fiscal year begins july 1
the cash-saving measures include delaying payments to government retirement systems, holding state income tax refund checks for 90 days and pushing one state payday back
in the meantime, roemer said he will cut the budget back as far as he can before the subject of taxes is broached
we are not going to raise taxes or change taxes until we cut this budget,'' roemer said. ``it is out of control.'' weapons</head>
a top taiwanese nuclear scientist has disappeared and may have fled to the united states with confidential blueprints disclosing that taiwan plans to make nuclear weapons, newspapers reported sunday
government officials repeatedly have denied any plans to produce nuclear weapons and said all nuclear research programs in taiwan are for peaceful purposes
on friday, defense minister cheng wei-yuan told the lawmaking legislative yuan that a warrant had been issued for the arrest of col. chang hsien-yi, 45, who was deputy director of the nuclear energy research center at the military-run chungshan institute of science and technology
cheng said the warrant was issued because chang had not asked permission for leave
chang has been missing since january, and officials said they have no information on his whereabouts
but the mass circulation united daily news said chang's daughter, pei-fen, wrote from georgia to a classmate at an elementary school in taipei last month saying she missed taiwan
the letter gave no return address and the girl gave no indication whether she was living with her father, the newspaper said
without disclosing the source of their information, several newspapers claimed that chang was a u.s. spy and had fled to the united states together with his wife and three children
the liberal newspaper independence morning post, quoting an unidentified institute official, said chang earlier had collected ``a whole bunch'' of pictures and confidential information on taiwan's nuclear plans
some newspapers said taiwan may have recycled key elements from waste from its three nuclear power plants to make nuclear weapons
the united daily news, quoting an unidentified source, said the united states may have become suspicious of taiwan's plans and this may have been behind a u.s. decision earlier this year to stop supplying taiwan with heavy water, which is needed for nuclear development
officials were unavailable for comment because of the sunday holiday
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev will spend five days in this communist country studying economic and social problems that he hopes the soviet union can avoid as it embraces reform
yugoslavia, which has jealously guarded its independence from soviet power for 40 years, presents a picture of prosperity to a visitor from moscow. a crush of private automobiles in the capital and store windows displaying local and western-made consumer goods of every description make moscow's truck-cluttered streets and drab facades seem all the more barren
but the country's system of ``self-managed, market socialism'' is struggling with high inflation, high unemployment, widespread labor unrest and a paralyzing $20 billion debt to western creditors
and yugoslavia's leadership must constantly perform a delicate balancing act to prevent the country from being torn apart by nationalistic rivalries within its borders
gorbachev arrives here monday for a five-day visit that includes belgrade, the northern industrial city of ljubljana and the southern resort city of dubrovnik on the adriatic
the soviet leader, who has just marked the end of his third year in power, is trying to boost the soviet union out of economic stagnation. he has decentralized control over production and introduced market forces to shake workers and managers out of their notorious complacency
during his tour gorbachev may gain some pointers on his programs of ``perestroika,'' or restructuring of the soviet economy, and ``glasnost,'' which encourages more open expression of ideas for solving the nation's problems
with the development in recent years of a free-wheeling press and a mixed economy that encourages both private enterprise and central planning, yugoslavia offers something of a window on the future for the reform-minded soviet leader
runaway inflation and the government's powerless decrees aimed at curing the country's economic ills serve notice that the path may not be an easy one
in recent months, as ethnic minorities have attempted to take advantage of the soviet government's new tolerance to express their long-held grievances, gorbachev has faced challenges from nationalists of several stripes
despite some rioting and huge mass demonstrations in the southern republics of azerbaidjian and armenia, no soviet ethnic group has the strength that yugoslavian nationalities have used to guarantee each a share of governing power at the expense of the central authorities
gorbachev is the first soviet leader to visit yugoslavia since the death of josip broz tito in may 1980. tito broke with moscow in 1948 and steered a stubbornly independent course outside the soviet bloc
after being forced by a soviet-led blockade to open trade with the west, yugoslavia has since re-established economic ties with moscow
the soviet union today is yugoslavia's largest trading partner, with the yugoslavs importing primarily crude oil and other raw materials and exporting manufactured goods, including much-prized shoes, clothing and technology to the soviet union
a $1.4 billion trade surplus is a subject of concern in belgrade, but there has been speculation the soviets may agree to pay off their paper debt by building a subway system for the traffic-clogged yugoslav capital
the present yugoslav leadership, headed by an eight-member state presidency, has continued tito's independent political course, and yugoslavia remains an important nation in the non-aligned movement
gorbachev is expected to formally acknowledge that special status with the issuance during his visit of a joint declaration guaranteeing full yugoslavian independence
but in the context of his public statements in prague and to fellow communist leaders in moscow last year, the gorbachev declaration may signal more independence for other east european nations as well
the soviet leader has said his nation has no monopoly on the proper path to socialism, and reform-minded leaders elsewhere in eastern europe are expected to test his words with experiments aimed at reinvigorating their own economies
yugoslav deputy foreign minister, ilija djukic, has said the new soviet-yugoslav document would update previous declarations signed by the two countries in 1955 and 1956 and will ``further confirm principles of non-interference on the basis of equality and soveregnty.''
talks aimed at ending the afghan war are one day away from a soviet deadline for their completion, but a crucial dispute on who will run the country still stands in the way of a signed settlement
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said last month that soviet troops would begin withdrawing troops from afghanistan by mid-may if an agreement is reached by march 15. but sources close to the u.n.-sponsored negotiations say they don't view the deadline as rigid
delegations from the soviet-backed government in kabul and from pakistan, which is representing the afghan resistance, both say they are ready to extend the negotiations
u.n. undersecretary general diego cordovez, the talks' mediator, said he asked both sides to seek ``strengthened instructions'' during the weekend to prepare for monday's session
soviet troops intervened in afghanistan in 1979. an estimated 115,000 troops have been helping the government fight the u.s.-backed moslem guerrillas
the latest round, the longest since the talks began in 1982, opened with a confident mood on march 2. two days later, an accord was announced on an issue that had stalled negotiations for years, with both sides agreeing on a timetable and the basic logistics for withdrawing the red army troops
under that accord, the pullout would be completed within nine months after its start, with half of the troops leaving in the first three months. cordovez said later there remained no ``differences of substance'' that would bar tying up a peace package of agreements
the agreements include a bilateral agreement pledging the two countries to not interfere in each other's affairs and arrangements for the return of more than 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan.
but the quick pace of the early talks quickly ran into snags
pakistan's chief representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani, said the talks were ``inching slowly'' forward, but that he expected them to regain speed this week. he did not elaborate why
the soviet union and its kabul allies, represented at geneva by foreign minister abdul wakil, blame pakistan for holding up final agreement
they fault pakistan's insistence on linking the proposed settlement to the formation of a transitional government acceptable to the resistance. gorbachev has said that the makeup of the future government should be decided by the afghans themselves
pakistan is insisting on a transitional government that would allow for the safe return of anti-soviet refugees.
so far, noorani has given no indication that pakistan would drop its demand. but sources close to the talks said islamabad still hopes to strike a deal with afghanistan, perhaps on the timing of the establishment of a new government
but another issue had cast an increasingly larger shadow on the talks: superpower aid to the two opposing sides
on march 4, the united states demanded that all foreign military aid to the warring parties must stop simultaneously. the soviet union has flatly rejected the demand, saying the accords will leave it free to continue military aid to kabul after the troop withdrawal
wakil said the draft agreements provide only for a cessation of military aid to the u.s.-backed guerrillas
in a strong statement on friday, state department spokesman charles e. redman said u.s. aid to the afghan rebels will not be halted until the soviets stopped their assistance to the kabul government. the soviets sent troops into afghanistan in 1979 to prop up the wobbly marxist government
the guerrillas, meanwhile, have formed their own government and have rejected any power sharing with the soviet-backed government of president najib
islamabad, pakistan (ap) _ pakistan's tough stand at the slow-moving afghan peace talks has touched off a power struggle among guerrilla leaders fighting the soviet-backed afghan government
pakistan prime minister mohammad khan junejo has been barnstorming the country to drum up support for his demand that an accord on a soviet troop withdrawal be coupled with a plan for a future kabul government
in the meantime, the fractious guerrilla alliance, whose factions all want a voice in that new government, has been plagued by upheaval. during the weekend, yunis khalis resigned as chairman of the seven-party alliance, ostensibly for health reasons
but there were numerous reports, unconfirmed by guerrilla spokesmen, that the 69-year-old khalis quit to protest plans to send a resistance delegation to the u.n.-sponsored peace talks at geneva, which resume monday
another insurgent leader, sibghatullah mojaddedi, pulled his moderate afghan national liberation front out of the alliance complaining of undue pressure from the body's four-party majority of moslem extremists
two days later, mojaddedi returned to the fold, saying he had received ``certain assurances'' from the fundamentalists and from pakistani officials. he did not elaborate
there has been intense pakistani pressure on the guerrillas to come up with an acceptable plan for forming a transitional government that would preside over the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops who back kabul's communist rulers
pakistan, which for years insisted the soviet presence was the root of the afghan conflict, reversed itself this year by declaring it would not sign an agreement that does not address afghanistan's political future
islamabad speaks for the guerrillas at the geneva talks and cares for about 3.5 million afghan refugees living in camps near the afghan border. it also channels u.s. arms to the guerrillas, who are headquartered in the northwest pakistani city of peshawar
although moscow and kabul have accused islamabad of blocking what could be an imminent soviet pullout, junejo's public relations campaign indicates pakistan's stand has solid public support
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev has said his troops could begin going home on may 15 if islamabad and kabul sign an agreement by march 15
the deadline pressure has taken its toll on the guerrilla alliance. while rejecting the geneva talks because of the guerrillas' exclusion, the alliance nevertheless responded with a proposal for a heavily moslem government headed by alliance leaders
mojaddedi protested when the extremists used their majority to vote in one of their own as future president, ahmed shah of the ittehad party
the moderate factions favor a compromise government that could include some communists now in power in kabul, possibly headed by former king zahir shah. mojaddedi insisted that the 73-year-old monarch, currently in exile in rome, is the only neutral figure acceptable to a majority of afghans
khalis's resignation, meanwhile, threatened to widen the split because the next leader in line for the rotating chairmanship is gulbaddin hekmatyar, head of the hezb-i-islami and the most extremist moslem guerrilla of all
while fending off acusations that his fighters have attacked rival groups inside afghanistan, hekmatyar recently had taken to upstaging khalis by calling press conferences of his own to promote hezb-i-islami's hardline vision of a fundamentalist islamic regime
mohammad uaqub sharafat, press spokesman for the alliance, said there were plans to send a guerrilla delegation to the geneva talks to help clear up the confusion over the insurgents' stand
even that move threatened to cause a rift
rasul sayyaf, leader of the ittehad party, issued a statement sunday declaring his opposition to sending a delegation
and under no circumstances shall we agree to any kind of direct or indirect talks with the kabul regime or the (ruling people's democratic party of afghanistan),'' he said
pakistani officials publicly have urged the guerrillas to soften their stand in the interest of peace. but so far, the extremists among the insurgents have equated compromise with capitulation
