lev timofeyev told the associated press that the 70 people who did attend the unsanctioned weekend seminar issued a statement condemning the ``unreasonable and irresponsible'' behavior of police agencies in detaining would-be participants
timofeyev, a moscow human rights activist, said the group that met at his southern moscow apartment learned that seven activists from lithuania, georgia, estonia and the ukraine were taken off of trains and planes headed for the capital
at least five others were told they shouldn't leave their homes over the weekend or they would be arrested, timofeyev said. among those kept under house arrest was genrikh altunyan, an armenian activist who lives in the ukrainian city of kharkov
armenia and the neighboring republic of azerbaijan have been the scene of the most intense unrest among the soviet union's more than 100 ethnic groups
a dispute over control of a region in azerbaijan known as nagorno-karabakh, where more than three quarters of the population is armenian, triggered mass demonstrations in yerevan in recent weeks and rioting in the azerbaijani city of sumgait that killed at least 32
timofeyev, who was released from a labor camp a year ago following a government review of political sentencings, said the seminar adopted three resolutions that will be forwarded to the kremlin on how to resolve ethnic problems
the first demands broad public discussion of ethnic tensions to correct widespread ignorance of the causes of nationalistic outbursts
another calls for discussion of limitations on religious freedom and the government's propagation of atheism, which the activists said is the root of some ethnic turmoil
the third proposal calls on the soviet government to let crimean tatars return to their historic homeland, the black sea peninsula from which they were routed during world war ii when dictator josef v. stalin accused the entire population of collaborating with nazi invaders
the tatars were exonerated two decades later, but they have been banned from returning to the crimea, now the site of some of the best resorts and official retreats
he said the documents produced at the seminar would be circulated among activists so the ``unofficial viewpoint'' on nationalities questions can reach the soviet public
the floods of vacationing students that once deluged this seaside community each spring have gone, leaving some hoteliers broken and the city rethinking its economy
only 100,000 college students are expected to bask this year on the subtropical sands, made famous in the 1960 movie ``where the boys are.'' there were 350,000 in 1985
the loss of business has prompted 12 smaller hotels that depended on the student crush to auction off their properties together april 7, said joe demastry of the fisher auction company
having paid top dollar for hotels in the early 1980 boom years, many of them now cannot meet their mortgage payments. by selling en masse, they hope to gain high prices by offering developers the opportunity to assemble large tracts
the unmanageable hordes of sunworshipping students, who packed hotel rooms by night and patronized businesses on the beach strip by day, divided this resort town
beach-front nightspots, vendors and student-dependent hotels clamored for continued promotion of spring break
but their cries were overcome by the din of residents and year-round businesses, snarled in springtime traffic and furious about paying for police and cleaning up mountains of trash
since 1986, when city leaders used strict law enforcement to quell the riotous partying, the city and broward county have been trying to diversify their tourist clientele
last year, word of strict police enforcement of parking, drinking, and code regulations discouraged student visitors, costing merchants $40 million and 100,000 student customers. the broward county tourist development council said the 200,000 student visitors spent about $80 million, one-third less than the $120 million tally from 1986, in the fort lauderdale area
police made about 1,300 arrests during last year's spring break, with college students comprising about one-third of them. there were 2,506 arrests in 1986
fort lauderdale is experiencing a ``shaking out,'' said roger handevidt, who plans to sell his orton terrace apartment hotel at the auction
what's happened is the city has said, `whoa! we can't deal with this,''' handevidt said of spring break. ``it was bad in 1985. i don't know anyone who would say differently.''
the atmosphere of drunkenness, littered streets and the stench from people urinating in the streets drove people away, he said
the money's just not coming in, so people are selling out,'' said the manager of a small hotel, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``we're losing money every week.''
fort lauderdale and broward county cannot depend on a seasonal tourism, officials said. the beach businesses are beginning to understand that, said nickie grossman, broward county commissioner and chairwoman of the tourism and development council
we want every tourist'' _ from new york yankees fans during baseball's spring training to miami dolphins fans and the teams the dolphins play at nearby joe robbie stadium, she said
but spring break is not dead in fort lauderdale. many students still come to this palm-dotted shore, warmed beneath 80-degree skies and bathed by 78-degree surf
we have a tradition at `lyco' that for the last three years we've won first place at the button (nightclub) drinking, wet t-shirt and guys' bikini contests. and we kept that tradition alive today,'' said dave gibbons, one of 15 sigma pi fraternity brothers visiting from lycoming college in williamsport, pa
only one ``small'' incident interfered with the fraternity vacation, gibbons said. ``we've got another buddy i tried unsuccessfully to bail out of jail today _ and get this _ the charge was throwing dangerous missiles, trespassing and disorderly conduct for picking up a table with cups on it and throwing it over a balcony.''
