the list includes some of waldheim's subordinates and superiors when he was an officer in the german army from 1939 to 1945, says jack saltman, who is producing the show for broadcast on u.s. and overseas television in june
it took a lot of persuasion to get some of them to do it,'' saltman said in a recent interview
with cameras rolling, lawyers will spend nine days beginning april 13 examining witnesses as if they were in a court of law, before a panel of retired jurists, including shirley hufstedler, a former u.s. education secretary and federal appeals court judge
the program then will be edited down to four hours, ending with the judges' decision on whether there is probable cause that waldheim acted contrary to the international laws of war
nobody has any idea how it will come out,'' saltman says. ``there's astonishingly little control over it. that's the beauty of it.''
the show is the latest entrant in what waldheim himself has called a new ``cottage industry'' _ investigating whether the austrian president knew about, supported or took part in atrocities when he served the germans in yugoslavia and greece during the war
since the investigations began with a probe by the world jewish congress in 1986, waldheim has been denounced around the world, been placed on a list of undesirables banned from entry to the united states and has become the focus of a bitter debate in his homeland
waldheim has denied taking part in atrocities. indeed, saltman says that in preparing for the show, he talked to the austrian leader for nearly an hour to get waldheim's side of the story
what did waldheim think of being ``tried'' on television? ``he was not overjoyed,'' saltman said. ``i don't think i'll be getting a christmas card this year from kurt waldheim.''
nor will waldheim appear on the program
work for the show began in may 1987, when producers at britain's thames television decided to do to waldheim what was done several years ago on a program called ``the trial of lee harvey oswald''
that was a mock courtroom proceeding, using real attorneys, judges and witnesses to the shooting of president kennedy in dallas in 1963 to determine if oswald was guilty of the crime
for aesthetic and legal reasons and because the participating witnesses and lawyers would have objected, saltman and his colleagues at thames television and co-producing home box office cringe when anyone uses the word ``trial'' when describing what they are doing to waldheim
they want to avoid comparisons with the daily syndicated u.s. show, ``people's court,'' where a real judge settles such issues as ``the case of the busted headlight.''
the show will be a ``commission of inquiry,'' with retired jurists from the united states, britain, india and sweden hearing testimony elicited by a ``presenting counselor,'' allan a. ryan, former director of the u.s. office of special investigation _ the justice department's nazi-hunting wing
lord peter rawlinson, britain's attorney general from 1970 to 1974, will be the ``challenging counsel,'' trying to rebut the evidence against waldheim
the proceedings will be filmed in a courtroom built for the program. then the judges will deliberate privately for as long as they think necessary and then deliver their opinions to the cameras a few days before the show goes on the air
like the u.s. supreme court, they may not agree. and like the high court, no one _ not even the producers _ will be allowed to hear the deliberations
the rules of evidence will be similar to those used in grand jury proceedings and the judgment will not be whether waldheim is guilty, but whether there is enough evidence to bring an indictment
this is about as close as anyone is going to get to bringing the waldheim case into a court of law,'' saltman said
no matter what we call it, the audience is going to say `this is the trial of kurt waldheim' and they're going to sit at home, and decide if he's a fascist,'' the producer said
according to evidence already made public, waldheim was a german intelligence officer familiar with reprisals against civilians to stop guerrilla activities in yugoslavia. questions have also been raised about whether he was involved in deportation of greek jews to death camps and mistreatment of allied prisoners of war
the controversy has been heightened by the fact that for many years, notably during his years of service as united nations secretary general, waldheim omitted all mention of his service in greece and yugoslavia in his official biography
saltman said a team of investigators hired by the producers scoured archives and searched for witnesses in austria, germany, italy, yugoslavia, greece, britain, bulgaria, albania, israel and the united states
so far, stations in france, scandinavia, israel, italy and australian have said they will show the program. negotiations with a west german station are underway. austrian television has also been offered a chance to buy the program, but there's no sign it will do so, saltman said
lawmakers hoping to make michigan the first state to ban the sale of realistic-looking toy guns are stockpiling ammunition to fight opponents, including toy makers and retailers lobbying against the bill
merchant groups are pushing to have any law take effect in 1991 so they can unload their plastic armories over three christmas seasons, instead of two
toy makers argue that any legislative remedies should come from congress, not the states, so manufacturers don't have to make 50 different types of toy machine guns to fit the requirements of each state
i think it would be a mass of total confusion if you regulate an interstate industry in a non-uniform manner,'' said aaron locker, general counsel for the toy manufacturers of america
against that backdrop, detroit police officer david malhalab told the michigan house consumers committee last week that the legislature must deal with the problem soon
i urge you to lead the nation. don't wait for congress,'' malalab said. ``by the time you come up with something, more children are going to be killed.''
malhalab brought a cache of the look-alike weapons to show the committee just how realistic the toys can look. he asked for laws requiring markings on the toys to make it easier for police officers to make split-second decisions
make it a different color. make it red. make it blue. make it yellow,'' malhalab said
the renewed call for a ban on the look-alike toys was sparked by the feb. 19 shooting death of a 13-year-old retarded boy in california. he was gunned down by san francisco police officers who mistook his plastic pistol for the real thing
a week later, 57 michigan house members co-sponsored a bill requiring the barrel of any toy firearm to be permanently sealed and colored in an ``indelible fluorescent orange.''
but legislators also were considering if the ban were in place how they would prevent criminals from copying the markings on fake guns and possibly tricking police into letting down their guard
rep. timothy walberg said he's afraid officers might see a potential cop-killer with a colored gun and develop a false sense of security
(criminals) are creative people. i see no problem with them taking a live weapon and painting it orange,'' walberg said
burbank, calif., became the first city in the nation to ban the sale of any toy that resembles a real weapon last september
two avalanches sunday crushed houses in this mountanous region under a mass of snow, killing seven people and injuring about 20, authorities said
no americans were among the dead
in italy, meanwhile, an italian skier was killed when he was buried by an avalanche on ski slopes near the swiss border, authorities reported
the snowslides in austria followed three avalanches in the same region saturday that killed three people
sunday's avalanches roared down mt. zwoelferkopf shortly after dawn, engulfing a gas station and several houses before they blocked a nearby railroad track, minutes after a train had passed the area
the avalanches occurred in st. anton in tyrol province, a well-known skiing area that has traditionally attracts scandinavian and british tourists
the massive snowslides ripped off roofs and crushed or tore off walls of houses, some of which have stood there for 300-400 years, a policeman said
authorities said five swedish tourists and two austrians were killed and about 20 others were injured. the identities of victims and the injured were not released
in innsbruck, the provincial security police headquarters put the fatality figure in this weekend's avalanches in the tyrol at 10, saying no more people were believed hidden under the rubble and snow at st. anton
some of the swedes were said to have been buried by collapsing walls of a boarding house, one of several buildings seriously damaged by the snow
policemen said the two avalanches had a combined length of about 1,200 feet and a height of up to 33 feet
in sondrio, italy, a rescue dog located the body of giuseppe rini, 37, after his wife came down the mountain to report the avalanche, the italian news agency ansa said
saturday, per-anders lundborg, a 24-year-old swedish tourist from hoerby, was killed, also near st. anton. he was part of a group of five swedish skiers who triggered an avalanche in an area barred from skiers
also on saturday, 17-year-old gerda schumacher from groenebach, west germany, was buried and killed by masses of snow when an avalanche hit seven people near a ski lift in the town of biberwier, tyrol province
two strollers were hit by a 1,500-foot-wide avalanche at berwang, tyrol province, saturday. eckehard leupold, 46, of duisburg, west germany, was rescued from the masses of snow, but his wife, erika, died
in tyrol and westernmost vorarlberg province, up to 45,000 tourists, many of them foreigners, were stranded sunday after heavy weekend snowfalls and a series of avalanches blocked many roads in the region
vorarlberg was completely cut off from the outside after an avalanche disrupted rail traffic on saturday, and the only exit out of tyrol province was the kufstein checkpoint on the border with west germany
motoring clubs said the line of cars traveling northward reached more than 15 miles in length
traffic conditions were chaotic in most parts of western austria, including the province of salzburg where many roads had to be closed after half a dozen snowslides
pope john paul ii is calling on the faithful to observe st. patrick's day, celebrating ireland's patron saint, by praying for peace in the emerald isle
the pope appeared sunday in st. peter's square to say the noon prayer before a crowd of some 25,000 and recalled his 1979 visit to the shrine to the virgin mary at knock, ireland
i invite you to pray so that in the land of st. patrick there is an end to the political and terrorist violence that for almost 20 years has been causing death and suffering both in the catholic and the protestant community,'' the pope said
since the resumption of sectarian violence in the british-ruled province of northern ireland in 1969, a total of 2,628 people have been killed, including 10 this year
the predominantly roman catholic irish republican army is fighting a guerrilla war to oust the british from the mainly protestant province and unite it with the irish republic to the south
prince edward, the youngest son of queen elizabeth ii, reportedly has proposed to the daughter of a belgian baroness _ a marriage that would require the prince to forfeit his chance to become king
the people, a weekly london tabloid, said the 24-year-old prince has proposed to georgia may, 22, whose mother catherine was born a baroness in belgium's van den branden de reeth family
edward would have to give up his rights as fifth in line to the british throne if he marries miss may, a roman catholic, the newspaper said
britain's 1701 act of settlement rules that only protestants may become british monarchs
the newspaper said the prince is awaiting the queen's permission to be formally engaged
it quoted miss may's former boyfriend, new zealand yachtsman ed danby, as saying she told him of the engagement plan in a telephone call last week
the people said the prince met miss may at a yachting regatta in cowes in southern england last august
former ``cbs morning news'' co-host phyllis george is taking on the small screen again with a one-hour television special on babies
the former miss america taped the show with prominent pediatrician t. berry brazelton in front of about 100 people, many of them her friends
george, who is married to former gov. john y. brown jr., left cbs 2{ years ago under a barrage of criticism
after tuesday's taping, george said she was pleased. ``i enjoy television. i enjoy people,'' she said. ``it was good for me to get back out and do something.''
george said she has had several television offers since she left cbs, but nothing has been quite right
regarding her cbs experience, george said: ``it was a great opportunity. it was a wonderful experience and i learned from it. and that's all i'm going to say.''
the baby special, ``phyllis george presents: brazelton on babies,'' will be aired sometime in april
country music singer larry gatlin, who sings the praises of a drug-free lifestyle, will receive the university of houston's distinguished alumni award
gatlin majored in english and also studied law at the university, which he attended in the late 1960s on a football scholarship. he will be honored by the school may 12
in recent months, gatlin has spearheaded anti-drug efforts in high schools. prior to that, he received treatment for cocaine use
he performs with his brothers steve and rudy and is known for hits such as ``all the gold in california'' and ``houston.''
singer joan baez, whose voice came to be synonymous with the peace movement in the 1960s, received the medal of peace award from the mayor of verdun
mayor jacques barat-dupont presented the medal saturday night following a concert, part of a french tour by the singer
verdun's medal of peace was instituted for the 50th anniversary of the battle of verdun in 1916. the northeastern french city was the site of heavy fighting during world war i
most recipients are war veterans or from cities which have known the terrors of war, like hiroshima, japan, or warsaw, poland
actress patricia neal says she and gary cooper wept after deciding to abort a child they conceived out of wedlock and she continued to weep about the decision for another three decades
for over 30 years, alone, in the night, i cried,'' she writes in her autobiography, ``patricia neal: as i am,'' excepts of which were published in the april issue of good housekeeping
if i had only one thing to do over in my life, i would have that baby,'' miss neal says
she and cooper were attracted to each other during filming of the movie, ``the fountainhead,'' according to the 62-year-old actress, who was 24 at the time. after filming ended, their love affair began, she said. cooper was living with his wife and daughter at the time
sharing a life with gary was not complex,'' miss neal wrote. ``i knew i had no rights with him. i did not allow myself then to consider the possibility of a permanent relationship. we were not building a future together. we were seizing moments.''
moscow _ a newspaper sunday questioned whether officials acted properly by ordering a hijacked aeroflot jet to land on soviet territory, pointing out that nine people were killed, 19 injured and the plane burned to ashes
an 11-member family jazz band from the siberian city of irkutsk seized the plane on tuesday as it headed across the ural mountains, soviet reports said. they demanded to be flown to london
the aeroflot crew duped the air pirates into believing they were landing in finland, but set down at a small airstrip near leningrad
the hijackers, led by a matriarch in her 50s who had been honored as a hero-mother of the soviet union, shot and killed a stewardess when they realized they had been deceived and set off a bomb after two hours of negotiations when a police assault team stormed the plane. five of the hijackers were killed, soviet reports said
sunday's edition of komsomolskaya pravda, the communist party youth newspaper, said the hijackers would have faced trial in britain if their demands to be flown there had been granted
we are entitled to a question: wasn't the price too costly for the decision to detain the bandits on our territory?'' the newspaper asked. ``an answer to this question lies with the courts.''
in calculating the cost of the incident, komsomolskaya pravda said ``the aircraft burned to ashes, nine people, including five of the criminals, were killed, and 19 people, including two on the assault team, were wounded, and many will be crippled for life.''
previous reports said the hijackers detonated a bomb in the tail section, setting fire to the plane, but the extent of the damage had not been made clear
the report said the police assault team had plenty of time to prepare before the tupolev-154 landed, but it implied that the preparations were inadequate
among the 76 passengers on board, three were killed and 32 surgical operations were needed among the 19 wounded, the newspaper said
it said one passenger's face was smashed with the butt of a submachine gun in the melee that ensued on the ground when people began jumping from doors and windows to flee the fire
a criminal investigating team has been assigned to the case, and the official tass news agency has reported that the surviving hijackers are in custody. accuracy</head>
rep. les aspin said sunday the air force is ``part of the problem'' in the guidance system for the mx missile, but the service says once again the weapon is reliable and accurate
the wisconsin democrat, chairman of the house armed services committee, said his panel's investigation of the 10-warhead weapon shows there are still problems in producing the missile's inertial measurement unit (imu), or guidance system
aspin's latest criticism of the mx was contained in a speech he plans to deliver on the house floor monday. a text of the speech was released sunday
aspin has previously criticized northrop, which is building the imus at a hawthorne, calif., plant
documents recently received by the house armed services committee show that while northrop is undeniably having its difficulties, the air force is part of the problem,'' according to aspin's speech
he said the documents, obtained from persons whom he did not identify, show that the service considered accepting one imu without inspecting it, and also protested the use of a process exempting small components from testing
an air force spokesman, capt. jay defrank, said, ``we stand by the imu's reliability and accuracy. we've answered many of the charges in his statement. there is nothing new there.''
the mx is the centerpiece of president reagan's nuclear build-up. reagan originally wanted to build 100 of the missiles and put them in silos in wyoming and nebraska, but congress limited the total deployment to 50 because of fears about the weapon's vulnerability to a soviet strike
the air force now wants to build 50 more and put them aboard trains. defense secretary frank c. carlucci has said he would like to put all 100 of the weapons aboard trains
the mx weapons tested thus far have shown better-than-expected accuracy, and the air force has consistently defended the ability of the weapons deployed to hit their targets
thus far, 34 mx weapons have been deployed, but only 22 have the proper imus. the other dozen still lack guidance systems, defrank said
northrop has promised to accelerate production of the guidance systems, and all 50 of the mx weapons are scheduled to be deployed by the end of 1988
one of the imus cited by aspin failed after only 200 hours on alert atop an mx missile, according to his speech. that would mean that it fell far short of the service standard of 3,000 hours allowed between failures, he said
but defrank said the 3,000 hours is a standard mean time, meaning it is an average. ``to criticize the air force for one imu failing is meaningless because it's the mean time between failures that is important, and we're meeting that,'' he said
agents from the pentagon planted listening devices in an apartment of panamanian military leader manuel antonio noriega several years ago, but the bugs failed to pick up any meaningful data, according to book excerpts published sunday
the noriega bugging story is one detail in a widespread secret effort by the pentagon that included efforts to rescue u.s. hostages, aid the contras in nicaragua and collect information on potential enemies around the world, according to ``secret warriors: inside the covert military operations of the reagan era,'' excerpted in u.s. news &amp; world report
the book by the magazine's senior editor, steven emerson, says the pentagon set up several secret units to carry out covert paramilitary operations after the failure of the 1980 attempt under president carter to rescue american hostages in iran
it says some of the operations were not disclosed to congress or to senior officials
the lack of coordination that led to the failed mission prompted the new administration to establish snow bird, to be run by a group of men in the army's new special operations division, says the book
emerson said his findings are based on a yearlong investigation, including information from hundreds of interviews and thousands of documents obtained under the freedom of information act
the noriega microphones were planted in 1983 by a defense department group called the quick reaction team, which specialized in electronic surveillance, according to emerson
the agents initially tried to bug noriega's luxurious residence, but they were scared off by barking dogs and guards who opened fire, the book says
another attempt met with better results,'' the report said. ``qrt agents succeeded in planting a bug in a lavish noriega apartment. but six tapes, each 90 minutes long, failed to yield any significant intelligence on noriega.''
the united states is now applying massive economic sanctions, including a freeze on panama's bank assets, in an effort to force noriega's resignation. the general also has been indicted on drug charges by a federal grand jury
other findings from emerson's book include:
_u.s. officials negotiated with the palestine liberation organization and libyan intermediaries to obtain the release of americans being held in lebanon, according to classified portions of private notebooks of fired marine lt. col. oliver north, a national security council aide who was a central figure in the iran-contra affair
one plan, which later collapsed, called for $10 million in covert payments to sheik fadlallah, the leader of the hezbollah organization holding the hostages and hussein massawi, the leader of the islamic amal militia. at u.s. request, the plo actually transferred some money to fadlallah to get the hostages out, but nothing happened
_in 1985, u.s. intelligence identified the location of the house where five of the six american hostages were being held in lebanon. the site was reconstructed by u.s. intelligence agents as part of a portable mini-model used by u.s. officials to prepare a rescue operation. a detailed military rescue mission was planned, but it was scrapped when the iran-contra affair began to unfold
_nsc sources said the man behind the kidnapping of the hostages was a shiite named immad mughniye. however, north said that mughniye's wife, whose relative was being held in a kuwaiti prison for terrorism, was running the show. ``ollie said mughniye wasn't going to get any sex until his (wife's relative) was released,'' says one excerpt from the book
_pentagon agents who discovered the soviets had ordered a fleet of opel automobiles in 1983 entered the manufacturing plant at night, took apart a car and embedded a transmitter in the frame. agents were then able to trail the car without being seen. ``the mission was so successful that a number of soviet agents were identified and several russian codes were broken.'' were there</head>
rep. richard gephardt's trademark boy scout smile froze as he peeked from behind the curtains at the sunrise musical theatre
stretching out beyond the stage he was about to take was a sea of empty seats _ no more than 400 people were at the 4,200-seat theatre. he could see some people walking out of the florida community association meeting, following the end of the featured speech by former president gerald ford
gephardt shook his head slowly, straightened himself, then strode out to give his campaign speech
it was a foreboding beginning to the final, three-day push to super tuesday, the 20-state set of primaries and caucuses that could have dramatically boosted the presidential ambitions of the missouri congressman
instead, on wednesday morning gephardt awoke to newspaper headlines that called him the day's big democratic loser
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis won the big prizes of texas and florida and five other states; civil rights leader jesse jackson won five states and the biggest share of the popular vote, and tennessee sen. albert gore jr., the candidate gephardt's campaign officials hoped to see eliminated tuesday, was stronger than ever after winning six states
gephardt won only one state _ missouri _ and finished fourth in 13. he was left with one last chance _ the march 26 michigan caucuses _ to keep his campaign alive
gephardt arrived here three days before super tuesday from louisiana, where his campaign's polls had said he was running neck-and-neck with jackson for the lead. polls in oklahoma and arkansas also were encouraging, and texas seemed volatile enough to take from dukakis with gephardt's theme of correcting the trade imbalance and spurring domestic oil production with an oil-import fee
in south florida, even though gephardt had the active support of the popular 87-year-old rep. claude pepper, the condominium community retirees were solidly for dukakis. after the musical theatre appearance, gephardt and pepper campaigned at condominium complex. fewer than 75 people turned out
next was the annual strawberry festival in plant city. it was raining as gephardt walked through the carnival-style grounds, and he attracted little attention. two days later, dukakis would arrive to hundreds of supporters, 500 dukakis signs along the route and a plane flying overhead with a dukakis streamer
in tallahassee, gephardt was joined by media consultant robert shrum, given credit for helping gephardt develop the populist theme that played so well in iowa. arriving in brownsville, texas, late saturday, shrum was asked if his rare travel with the campaign was a sign of trouble
no, no, i just like to get out in the field sometimes,'' said shrum, smiling around his big cigar
gephardt began sunday with a taping of ``meet the press.'' the first questions were about his ``flip-flop'' on abortion. meanwhile, both gore and dukakis were attacking gephardt for changing positions on the issues. dukakis was running a commercial depicting a man in a business suit doing back flips, with a voice-over about gephardt's issue switches
later, as gephardt's motorcade with the long black limousine drove into the border city of texarkana, oncoming cars pulled over to the side of the road
a local gephardt supporter explained: ``they see the black car and they think it's a funeral procession. it's tradition that you pull off the road for a funeral.''
joe trippi, gephardt's deputy campaign manager, the campaign's ``spin'' specialist, was trying to put the best light on the upcoming super tuesday voting. on sunday, the spin was that even if gore and gephardt shared third place, it would be a victory for gephardt because his strength would be shown as comparable to gore's in the tennessee senator's southern stronghold
gephardt's showing, as it turned out, wasn't up to the spin
that night in dallas, gephardt invited the traveling press to join him at casa dominguez, where he had the mexican special combination dinner and a budweiser beer, brewed in his hometown of st. louis. gephardt talked about his beloved st. louis cardinals baseball team
someone asked: ``why didn't you stop in st. petersburg and take batting practice with the cardinals?'' gephardt smiled ruefully, doubtless thinking of rival dukakis' much-publicized visit to red sox camp in winter haven, where the governor donned a boston uniform and took some swings in the batting cage
that was a good picture, wasn't it?'' gephardt said
on monday, gephardt headed to san antonio, where dukakis had drawn 1,500 people a day earlier, addressing hispanic crowds in fluent spanish. no more than 400, many of them tourists, were there as gephardt spoke in front of the alamo, one day after the 152nd anniversary of the fall of the badly outmanned texan mission to the mexican army
gephardt concluded his texas campaign monday evening with a visit to the johnson space center, where he detailed his kennedyesque plan to revitalize the u.s. space program. but media questions concentrated on how he would do tuesday
asked whether any candidate could finish worse than third tuesday and survive, gephardt replied: ``i don't know ... i know i'm going to keep fighting to get my message out.''
as the campaign headed to miami, where its ill-fated super tuesday campaigning would conclude, trippi was talking spin again. he was talking about michigan
steno, an italian director of comedy films, died sunday from a stroke, italian news media reported
born in 1917, steno's real name was stefano vanzina
he began his career as a screenwriter in 1945 and soon after began directing comic films. some, such as ``guardie e ladri'' (guards and thieves), starred one of italy's best-loved comics, toto
there was no immediate word on survivors or funeral arrangements
mildred jeffrey, a wayne state university trustee for 12 years, and joseph f. rosenfield, a grinnell college trustee for 47 years, received the association of governing boards' distinguished service awards sunday
the awards, sponsored by the oil company b.p. america, include an inscribed steuban crystal bowl for the winners and $5,000 unrestricted grants to their institutions
ms. jeffrey was cited not only for her work at wayne state but for helping expand the michigan association of governing boards. michigan gov. james j. blanchard said she ``has made an historical and permanent mark on michigan's higher educational system.''
rosenfield was crediting with helping to spur the growth of grinnell's endowment over the past two decades from $11 million to $250 million. he was also credited with encouraging an aggressive minority recruitment program and planning for divestiture of south african investments
women now head nearly 300 of the accredited colleges and universities in the united states, the american council on education said sunday
the number of women college presidents doubled from 148 in 1975 to 296 in 1987, with the most rapid growth at public institutions, said the council's office of women in higher education
but the fastest spurt was in the late 1970s and early 1980s, it said. there was a net increase of only 10 women presidents between 1984 and 1987
there are more than 3,400 two- and four-year colleges in the united states; 2,880 are accredited
eighty-six of the women presidents, or 29 percent, are nuns heading religious institutions. forty, or 14 percent, are minorities, including 22 black, 13 hispanic, four american indian and one asian-american women
since 1984, the office said, the number of women heading four-year public institutions has increased 22 percent, from 32 to 39
the number heading four-year private colleges and universities grew by 16 percent, from 134 to 156
women also held the presidencies at 73 two-year public colleges (up from 72 in 1984) and 28 two-year private institutions (down from 48)
donna shavlik, director of the office of women in higher education, said colleges need to search harder and address inequities in hiring and promoting women. ``what's needed is personal and institutional commitment and determination to achieve the goal,'' she said. fights on</head>
when a campaign starts to slide, as bob dole's surely has, everything goes wrong, even the little things. the candidate finds himself struggling to overcome power failures and competing for attention against vanna white
the signs are everywhere that george bush has all but clinched the republican presidential nomination. he won a smashing victory on super tuesday and appeared poised to keep rolling on tuesday when illinois holds its primary
yet, despite the battering he has taken from bush in recent contests, dole clearly sees a loser when he looks at the vice president
sooner or later,'' he said sunday on the cbs show ``face the nation,'' ``the voters in one of these states are going to say, wait a minute, we're about to nominate a loser.''
but dole's view wasn't shared by many republican voters in the south and doesn't appear likely to find much support in illinois
in fact, if anyone looked like a loser, it was the senator from kansas
after super tuesday, dole needed a way to turn the race around. bush came out of the south with a big lead in delegates _ 705 to 165 _ but the next battleground was the midwest and dole had trounced bush in iowa, minnesota and south dakota
dole had his hands full as he started his illinois campaign, still stunned by the magnitude of his loss on super tuesday when bush took all 16 primaries
suddenly word got out that the campaign was laying off most of its paid staff and was pulling all its commercials off the air in illinois. rumors spread swiftly that dole was going to throw in the towel and concede the nomination to bush
that possibility clearly had been discussed and rejected
dole said people were laid off because ``a campaign is not a jobs program'' and after super tuesday, paid staff was not needed in a large number of states. while that argument made some sense, the timing of the layoffs, right after a big loss, left the unmistakable impression the campaign was folding
the announcement on the television commercials was a case of different people in the same campaign giving out conflicting versions of what was happening
william brock, the campaign manager, finally said on friday that all the commercials had not been pulled. he said many had been dropped in favor of a decision to buy 30 minutes of time for a major dole effort to win voter support
brock's version, as it turned out, was correct. some 30-second dole commercials are running in illinois. but the former secretary of labor was not around to provide an authoritative version when the word first got out. he was attending ceremonies marking the anniversary of the founding of the labor department
the 30-minute dole program, originating from knox college in galesburg, site of one of the lincoln-douglas debates, turned out to be a showcase of campaign disarray
eight hours before the program was to air, dole advisers were unable to say exactly what it would contain. aides were scrambling to fill the 30 minutes. nearly half of it was filled by a dole biography filmed months ago for showing at campaign events
the message the candidate delivered was a restatement of campaign rhetoric, his contention that bush was not discussing the issues
the issues are more important than the odds,'' he said, portraying himself as the one who was responsible for getting president reagan's program through congress
it was a $100,000 gamble _ and was all the riskier due to the decision to go live instead of taping the program in advance. in the middle of the program, there was an unexplained power failure that resulted in loss of the picture for several minutes. the sound was not interrupted
how many voters saw the program was questionable. it was competing against ``wheel of fortune,'' the popular game show in which vanna white has become a celebrity for her role of turning around the letters on word puzzles
while dole was fighting for attention in one campus building, bush was addressing a cheering crowd of more than 1,000 republicans in the college gymnasium about 200 yards away
tied as tightly as ever to reagan, bush condiently predicted, ``we are going to win on tuesday because we have the people with us.''
in the battle for republican primary votes, bush is looking and sounding very much like a winner
the associated press
inside an old brick building that once was a drive-in liquor store, a minister and a group of volunteers are putting the finishing touches on a cafe for people who rarely get to enjoy restaurant treatment
the cafe will be for the homeless, who have some of their basic needs met by the city's shelters and soup kitchens but are unable to enjoy the more relaxed and personal atmosphere of a restaurant, said the rev. a.b. short
i'm thankful for the feeding programs; they (the homeless) couldn't survive without them,'' said short, who has been involved in homeless aid programs since moving to atlanta in 1980
but if you feed 500 people in two hours, you can't give much personal attention,'' he said
short said the restaurant will be relatively small, serving about 30 at a time, and will emphasize a friendly atmosphere over merely providing food to the homeless
people have a need for food, but we hope the interaction and relationships will be our primary product,'' he said
the restaurant will feature counter service as well as tables. the kitchen will be entirely visible from the dining area so patrons can talk to the cooks, dishwashers and other volunteer staffers, short said
one of the main differences from the standard shelter kitchen will be that the homeless will be able to choose items from a menu, instead of just having plates of food handed to them
there will be no charge for the food, but a voucher system of tickets distributed by area shelters may be used, short said
a legal aid service as well as alcohol and drug abuse counseling also will be available on the premises, short added
there are an estimated 7,000-10,000 homeless in the atlanta area
renovation work began in november with the help of $30,000 in federal and state grants. several individuals and businesses have contributed materials or funds, and some of the work has been done by volunteers, including members of the homeless community
the idea seems so unique it has sparked a lot of people's interest,'' short said, adding that he hopes the restaurant will be ready to open by the end of the month
once it is open, much of the food will be provided by agencies that already help the homeless. short said he also will rely on donations to keep the restaurant going
at first, the restaurant will serve for two hours beginning at noon. short said he hopes he can add a breakfast or dinner period later
short, 43, a native of mississippi, said the idea for the restaurant grew from his involvement with the homeless, which started when he organized a shelter at oakhurst baptist church in suburban decatur, where he is a member
he said his church, which includes many social activists, responded enthusiastically to the shelter project. but he and his wife, who is on the faculty of emory university, wanted to go a step further
we decided that if we were really serious about the homeless issues, what we might ought to be doing is having homeless people live with us,'' he said
they have had homeless people living with them since 1982, and some of them now are working on the restaurant, located near the martin luther king jr. center for nonviolent social change
short said he does not envision facilities such as the restaurant replacing traditional shelters or kitchens, but he would like to see it become an established part of the homeless aid network
it's just another piece of the very important work people are already involved in,'' he said
