jesse jackson said sunday that winning in his native south carolina may give him the momentum in his adopted home state to upset illinois sen. paul simon in the primary here on tuesday
jackson won 54 percent of the vote saturday in south carolina's democratic caucuses and 23 of 44 delegates to the national convention
upon his return to illinois, jackson was greeted with the results of a chicago tribune poll indicating he was in a virtual dead heat with simon, the state's other favorite son
simon has ``the inside track'' and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis has the money, jackson said in a campaign stop at st. sylvester's, a roman catholic church in chicago's hispanic humboldt park neighborhood
so here i am again, the underdog with the big bite,'' he said
the latest associated press count shows jackson now has 423 delegates to 35 for simon, who sat out south carolina as well as last week's 20-state super tuesday contest
jackson and simon are battling for the 113 state democratic delegates to be elected tuesday. simon, who hails from southern illinois, has full delegate slates in all 22 congressional districts. jackson has slates _ although not all are full _ in all but one of the districts
i certainly hope to win the popular vote and the delegate vote in illinois,'' jackson said. ``i've been a builder in this state for 25 years and i hope the people with whom i stood will stand with me on tuesday
we will get support all over the state,'' he added
to ensure statewide support, jackson planned a rally sunday night in east st. louis, the state's other major black population center. on monday he planned to swing south to carbondale and travel through the fertile illinois farmland with stops in springfield and bloomington and finally chicago, where he owns a home
jackson was buoyed by the tribune poll results
that means in the last lap of the race, whoever has the most kick, whoever has the most strength in the last lap down the stretch will win,'' he said
asked about the possibility of throwing his support to democratic front-runner dukakis, jackson said he was too busy running and winning to give it a thought
the message is winning _ end economic violence against the farmers and workers, stop the flow of drugs into our country,'' jackson said
jackson is being asked these days about his chances against republican george bush in the general election, if they were their respective parties' nominees
he certainly has a lot of baggage,'' jackson said of the vice president on nbc's ``meet the press.''
