chuck pascale thought an exploding snail had blown his 5-year-old restaurant business to smithereens
instead, it brought nationwide fame
karen j. prouty was celebrating her 36th birthday with a dinner at pascale wine bar &amp; restaurant on feb 26. she was eating her second escargot when it blew up in her face
garlic butter caused minor burns around her right eye and blinded her for 90 minutes. prouty was treated at a hospital and released the same evening
the snail's internal moisture had apparently built up steam that propelled it right out of its depression in a ceramic serving dish, pascale theorized
pascale said he pleaded with the local newspaper not to print a story on the incident fearing it would hurt business. but he said the night the article was printed, escargot was the most popular item at the restaurant. every snail in the building was sold, he said
we've won national awards for four consecutive years, and we've been nominated for a fourth star in mobil travel guide,'' said pascale's brother and partner, neal pascale. ``but this definitely added to our national reputation.''
the pascale brothers and etienne merle are partners in the establishment, which specializes in french and northern italian cuisine
since the story was publicized nationally, the pascales have fielded about 30 calls from radio stations and newspapers around the country. friends and business associates have mailed them newspaper clippings about their exploding snail from los angeles, phoenix, milwaukee, new york, washington, miami and even mexico city
humorist dave barry plans to write about the incident for his nationally syndicated column april 17 in the miami herald
in the course of all the publicity, and after realizing prouty was not seriously hurt, the brothers said they have begun to accept the humor in the accident
now they quip about their flying snails and how they're training them to stay in the dish. nomination early</head>
jesse jackson on sunday was touting his big win in his native south carolina, while officials struggled to count the final ballots after a record turnout at democratic caucuses
about 45,000 voters turned out saturday, officials said
even as he celebrated his victory, jackson quickly turned his sights toward the next battleground _ illinois, which holds its primary tuesday
this is a 50-state marathon race and we're now moving into another lap,'' jackson said. illinois is jackson's adopted home state; the civil rights leader has been based in chicago for years
in a television interview, jackson suggested that at the rate he's going, he could lock up the democratic nomination before the convention in atlanta in july
i hope by that time to have a majority of the popular votes. i hope my delegate total will correspond to my popular vote and on that basis i hope to be the nominee of the party,'' he said from chicago on nbc's ``meet the press'' program
with 1,668, or 93 percent of south carolina's 1,788 precincts reporting, jackson had about 54 percent of the delegates to attend county conventions later this month. nineteen percent were uncommitted while tennessee sen. albert gore jr. collected 18 percent
masachusetts gov. michael dukakis collected 7 percent and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 2 percent
in terms of the 44 national convention delegates at stake saturday, jackson apparently will collect 23 while 15 will be uncommitted and six went to gore. there are also four so-called super delegates from the state
nationally, jackson's delegate total lags behind that of dukakis. the massachusetts governor has 460.5; jackson has 423.55
carol kahre of the state democratic party said the estimated turnout of 45,000 easily surpassed the old record of about 25,000 set back in 1976
she said it could be a couple of days before all the figures from the counties are tabulated
the problem now becomes the county party priorities are preparing for their county conventions,'' she said, adding state officials must ``beg a lot'' to get all the numbers in
there's no official state certification of the results, she said. the credentials of each delegate will be checked at the county conventions and then again at the state convention
the record turnout for the meetings ``slowed them up and slowed up the reporting. but that's a nice kind of problem to have,'' she added
earl black, a political science professor at the university of south carolina, said the record turnout was due to ``a flurry of final days campaign activity.''
i'm certain the proportion of black voters at the democratic caucuses was higher than the overall percentage of black voters'' in the state, he said. ``with south carolina being jesse jackson's home state, there was a very strong incentive in the black community.''
some of it was due to gore's showing on super tuesday. some democrats felt that there was (another) candidate out there they could support,'' black said
jackson, gore and gephardt all campaigned in the state in the days leading up to the caucuses
attorney general edwin meese iii said sunday the united states still lacks legal backing for a customs service plan to seize the passports of americans suspected of entering the country with illegal drugs
our legal people are working with customs and by the time that that program starts, we will have a legal basis for it,'' meese said on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley.''
william von raab, the customs service commissioner, announced march 2 at the white house conference on a drug-free america that his agency will take the passports of americans who try to re-enter the country with illegal drugs, beginning tuesday
customs service spokesman edward kittredge said the passports would be seized as evidence of a crime and forwarded to the state department
meese, questioned about a plan to shoot down planes used for drug trafficking, said the program lacks the necessary amount of certainty to determine whether a plane is carrying drugs
i think right now we do not have the capability of putting in an effective program _ a foolproof program of shooting down planes ... and therefore i am not in favor of it at this time,'' meese said
now that george bush has virtually locked up the republican presidential nomination, he is carefully putting some distance between himself and some elements of the reagan administration record
in a major switch in campaign strategy, bush also is trying to broaden his appeal to democrats and independents _ a massive block of voters that ronald reagan tapped successfully in 1980 and 1984
the vice president signaled this transition in tactics the day after his most impressive electoral performance ever _ a stunning sweep of the 16 gop primaries on super tuesday
the message will have to be fleshed out more, and more definitive,'' he said
craig fuller, bush's chief of staff, said ``we don't want to get out ahead of ourselves and launch a national campaign before we get the nomination. but i think you'll see him beginning to talk more about various issues.''
bush later departed abruptly from his basic stump speech
he told an audience of republican boosters in chicago thursday that if elected he would create a special white house office on ethics and devise a new ethics code. it was a concrete proposal on a general campaign theme he has pitched since last fall
i am tired of being embarrassed'' by news accounts of ethical misdeeds by government officials, he said
he said his call for a white house ethics office should not be taken as criticism of president reagan. he said he was talking about ``how i would do it.''
in another part of the speech, he offered details on how he would try to attack federal budget deficits _ going beyond a four-year, flexible spending freeze proposed earlier. he said he would take a ``hands-on'' role as a participant in negotiations with congressional leaders
the tower commission set up to investigate the iran-contra affair concluded, among other things, that policy-making went awry because of reagan's hands-off management style
bush had said early in his campaign that he intended eventually to talk of ``shades of difference'' in how he would approach things, as opposed to reagan. and that's what happened thursday
the chicago tribune, endorsing sen. bob dole over bush in the next day's newspaper, said:
nowhere have the republican candidates asked or answered the kind of harsh questions the democrats surely will raise in november about the reagan administration, whose colors mr. bush has been able to wave more furiously than anyone else.''
so, bush's decision to hammer away at the theme of lifting the level of ethics in government seems to be an attempt to position the candidate to better cope with the iran-contra issue, the investigations of attorney general edwin meese and the convictions of former white house officials michael k. deaver and lyn nofziger
campaign manager lee atwater said ``it was a big mistake'' for dole of kansas to continue running campaign advertisements questioning bush's role in supporting the arms-to-iran initiative. ``this has created a lot of resentment in the republican party,'' he said
but atwater and other top bush strategists know they have not heard the last of the issue, particularly in view of the continuing investigation of the iran-contra affair by special counsel lawrence e. walsh
bush could find himself trying to campaign against a democrat at a time when administration figures are being indicted and tried in connection with the scandal
the shift in bush's strategy apparently resulted from a conclusion that the vice president has sufficient strength _ with 705 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the nomination _ to shift toward a broader-based campaign
a dual purpose would be to lessen his vulnerability to criticism by a democratic opponent of the reagan administration's record on ethics and to reach out to blue-collar voters, democrats, independents and others who have supported president reagan in the past
i do think we'll reach out to ethnic groups and various minority groups,'' fuller said of the emerging bush strategy. ``he has consciously reached out to the hispanic population in the southwest and to cubans in florida. i think he will work very hard to capture ethnic groups.''
bush also can be expected to touch up his campaign pitch to appeal to workers _ as he did in acknowledging that not everyone has benefited from the economic recovery. he said the face of a jobless man in illinois looks just as grim as the face of a man out of work in savannah, ga
the storm system that dumped heavy snow on the plains had moved into canada and weakened sunday, and in its wake below-normal temperatures extended from the rockies to the appalachians
afternoon temperatures were below the freezing mark across much of the northern and central rockies, northern and central plains and the great lakes region
during the night, freezing temperatures were expected to extend as far south as much of texas and most of the lower mississippi valley, except the gulf coast. freeze warnings were posted for all of mississippi except coastal sections and for the hill country of southern texas
snow showers extended from the upper mississippi valley across the great lakes to the upper ohio valley. two to 4 inches of snow fell during the morning in snow belt areas near lake superior
a winter storm watch was posted for monday across extreme northeastern ohio near lake erie, with as much as 8 inches possible by monday night
freezing rain made travel hazardous over parts of inland northern new england during the morning, especially in some deeper valleys
elsewhere, light snow fell over much of the rockies during the afternoon. up to 4 inches fell in the mountains near alamosa, colo
showers diminished across the mid-atlantic states and the carolinas, but scattered thunderstorms broke out during the morning along coastal sections from north carolina to florida
heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 1 p.m. est included 1.15 inches at patrick air force base at cocoa, fla., and 1.00 inch at orlando, fla
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 9 degrees above zero at yellowstone national park to 87 at west palm beach, fla. the early morning low for the day was 19 degrees below zero at chadron, neb., and west yellowstone, mont
for monday, snow showers were forecast from new england across the northern and central appalachians and the ohio valley to the great lakes region. snow showers also were forecast from the northern and central rockies into the western dakotas. showers were forecast in southern florida
highs only in the teens were predicted in parts of upper michigan; in the 20s from northern vermont across northern and western sections of new york, pennsylvania and west virginia, the upper ohio valley, the great lakes and the upper mississippi valley to eastern sections of the dakotas; in the 50s or 60s from the southern atlantic coast across the gulf coast region, texas and much of the southwest to the pacific northwest; in the 70s and lower 80s in southern florida and from the desert southwest to most of california; and in the 30s or 40s in most of the rest of the nation
one man who died after a fall from a hotel balcony and a second injured hours later at the same hotel were not part of the annual invasion by out-of-state college students, police said sunday
with the onslaught of more than 300,000 college students on spring break, daytona beach authorities have been trying to crack down on such alcohol-related antics as climbing on motel balconies
in 1986, five died and seven were seriously injured in falls from high-rise motels in florida
on saturday, jay stricklin, 24, of orlando leaned over the railing of a fourth-floor sundeck at the seashore motel and lost his balance, police said. he was flown to halifax medical center, where he died of head injuries
two hours later, david baldwin, 19, of ocala fell off a second-floor roof onto the pool deck of the same hotel, and was rushed seriously injured to the same hospital
a friend told police that baldwin had been drinking all day, said police capt. noel ouellette
baldwin was in serious condition sunday with a concussion and facial injuries, said hospital spokeswoman charlotte hinson. with later government statement on casualties, compensation for victims, three sted two policemen killed</note>
hundreds of nepalese crowded hospitals sunday and looked for relatives after a sudden hailstorm caused a stampede at a soccer stadium, killing about 90 people and injuring scores
doctors at katmandu's main facility, the bir hospital, said about a dozen unidentified bodies could present a health hazard because there was no place to properly store them
we have no room in the morgue. there is in fact no morgue to speak of in medical terms,'' said one doctor, speaking on condition of anonymity
the stampede occurred saturday when a hailstorm struck during a soccer game at the national stadium. witnesses said the crowd of about 30,000 surged toward the one open exit, and many people were crushed or suffocated to death
government television reported 73 died, and witnesses said at least 20 other bodies were taken away by relatives for cremation. more than 100 people were treated at hospitals. three people remained in critical condition sunday
home affairs minister niranjan thapa said later sunday that 70 people perished in the tragedy, including three police officers. he said 94 people had been hospitalized with injuries, and 15 remained in serious condition
thapa denied reports that police charged crowds outside the stadium when they attacked government cars with rocks. witnesses said police used batons to club people enraged that other gates to the stadium had not been opened
the government ordered a judicial panel to investigate the disaster and said it would pay compensation to relatives of victims and to the injured
soccer is nepal's most popular sport, and saturday's game was the final match in a tournament between a team from the national tobacco factory and a team from bangladesh
government-run newspapers reported that the crowd surged toward the south exit _ where most people usually enter the stadium _ but made no mention of other doors being locked
they reported that king birendra and queen aishwarya visited the injured in hospitals
the official national news agency reported that the government declared a national day of mourning sunday, a normal working day, and ordered all sports events and other entertaintment canceled
at bir hospital, about a mile from the stadium, one patient, judha tamang said, ``i got blessing from our beloved king and queen.''
hundreds of anxious people crowded around one hospital building where pictures of the unidentified dead had been posted
bhayacha kumale, from thimi, just outside katmandu, said he lost two of his sons, aged 12 and 16, in the tragedy. a third son had decided to skip saturday's soccer game
i could not even give them a drop of water before they died,'' kumale said
in nepal, it is a tradition for relatives to gather at a dying person's bedside and give him water to comfort him
the stampede was nepal's worst sports-related disaster on record
it came just two days after part of a grandstand collapsed at the main soccer stadium in tripoli, libya, reportedly killed around 20 people during a match between libya and malta
some of the 60,000 spectators at the 75,000-seat ``june 11 stadium'' panicked when someone brandished a knife, news reports said
in the worst soccer disaster on record, rioting left nearly 300 people dead and 500 injured on may 24, 1964, in lima, peru, after argentina beat peru on a last-minute goal

