the indian government rejected the latest call for a cease-fire in sri lanka from a tamil rebel leader, saying his words did not match his deeds, an indian diplomat said sunday
he said the appeal by velupillai prabhakaran, issued saturday in the southern indian city of madras, was one ``of a series of communications we've received from time to time.''
he noted that prabhakaran's liberation tigers of tamil eelam had continued to attack rival tamil militants as well as indian forces sent to sri lanka last july to enforce a peace accord. the diplomat spoke on condition of anonymity
the tigers, the largest sri lankan rebel group, have refused to surrender their weapons as called for in the indian-sponsored peace plan signed by india and sri lanka. the pact was designed to end the tamils' nearly 5-year-old guerrilla war for an independent homeland in northern and eastern sri lanka
india has an estimated 50,000 troops in sri lanka to enforce the accord. prabhakaran has been in hiding since an indian offensive against his stronghold in sri lanka's northern jaffna peninsula began last october
in his statement, prabhakaran appealed for a cease-fire but said he was skeptical that sri lanka's sinhalese majority would abide by the peace accord
tamils, most of whom are hindus and who make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million population, claim they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese buddhists
india became involved in the sri lanka conflicet because of its tamil minority of 60 million tamils _ most of them in madras and surrounding tamil nadu state. although india has sent troops to sri lanka to enforce the peace pact, it has allowed the rebel groups to maintain exile offices in madras, 250 miles north of the island nation of sri lanka, formerly ceylon
in colombo, sri lankan police said 15 sinhalese had been arrested in connection with an ambush near the eastern port of trincomalee on friday in which 22 men, women and children were killed. most of the victims were tamils
in the northwest, two sinhalese serving in the sri lankan army were shot to death saturday 400 yards from the adampan military camp near mannar
military sources in colombo said the soldiers were slain by liberation tigers guerrillas. pipeline</head> trades involved $150,000.</note>
a memo by a longtime friend of attorney general edwin meese iii describes the two men joining in a 10-minute ``briefing'' of israeli prime minister shimon peres on a proposed $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
the memo by e. robert wallach, first disclosed in sunday editions of the washington post, says peres ``literally dragged me off into a corner'' and began discussing the pipeline ``intensely'' at an israeli embassy reception in washington on oct. 16, 1985
the document says that in the crush of activity at the reception, peres then asked wallach to wait until after the event to discuss the pipeline further
fortunately, as the time approached, my friend (wallach's usual phrase for meese) arrived and there was a three-way discussion which took approximately 10 minutes,'' said wallach's memo
he (peres) is very quick and we went right to the point and he was agreeable in all respects. it wasn't the kind of briefing i would have preferred, but it seemed to be effective,'' the memo said
meese, interviewed sunday on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley,'' denied the story, while foreign ministry officials in israel refused to comment on the latest report
the attorney general, asked if the report was correct, responded: ``no it's not. it's the usual thing you expect these days from the washington post, taking a small fact that is well known and trying to blow it up into a new news story.''
many times, at that particular reception i had brief conversations with prime minister peres,'' meese said. ``there's nothing new to it.''
meese also reiterated that he will not resign his post despite the growing controversy
obviously i shouldn't step aside because if honest public officials can be hounded out of office by partisan political attacks, by media barrages, then no one as a public official is safe,'' he said
the attorney general said that ``at no time has this (investigation) detracted from my ability to do my job.''
asked if he should step aside for president reagan's sake, meese said, ``i think it would hurt him. and i think it would hurt the cause of good government more if i didn't stand up and fight these false allegations because to leave would acknowledge that maybe there's some truth to them.''
on sunday, james rocap, one of meese's lawyers, said that ``wallach's account totally exaggerates'' the discussion ``in order to impress his (wallach's) client.''
wallach was legal counsel to swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the proposed project. two months before the embassy reception, rappaport had paid wallach $150,000, which wallach directed be sent to an account owned by w. franklyn chinn, an investment manager at the time for both wallach and meese
wallach's money was in effect pooled in several stock trades with meese's funds, sources familiar with a criminal investigation of meese, speaking on condition of anonymity, said friday
meese, asked about reports that he had profited from stock trades involving $150,000, said, ``i knew nothing about this money being paid.''
chinn's company had a separate financial arrangement with meese. the attorney general said that in any event his financial arrangements with chinn were set up as a limited blind partnership so that ``i had no way of knowing what was being done or how it was being managed.''
meese described wallach as ``my friend'' and said he ``never asked me to do anything that was wrong. ... in this case, a lot of people are taking a simple situation where i turned something over to the national security council staff and then for political reasons or media attack reasons they're trying to make a big deal out of it.''
in a statement issued feb. 1, meese said that his total involvement with peres on the pipeline consisted of ``only two contacts ... each was brief and limited and neither was initiated by me.''
a second memo by wallach, also described in sunday editions of the post, recounts a meeting in new york _ a few days after the embassy reception in washington _ involving peres, wallach, then-national security council aide david wigg and the israeli ambassador to the united states
wallach said the meeting lasted about 15 minutes and that the four discussed two proposed letters for peres to sign, the first committing israel not to disrupt the pipeline and the second dealing with the concepts of using u.s. foreign aid to israel as insurance for the project
peres has said he recalls having met wallach only twice, on social occasions with others present
peres eventually signed a later version of the first letter. peres said he could not act on a second letter without additional consultation in israel, wallach's memo said
the pipeline project collapsed shortly thereafter for lack of an insurance package. the justice department saw legal impediments to using israeli aid money
finally, national security adviser john poindexter, on the advise of former nsc adviser william clark, killed u.s. involvement in the project
meese's involvement with the proposed pipeline is under criminal investigation by independent counsel james mckay, who launched a probe of meese's activities last may 11
the two memos were obtained from wallach's files recently by mckay's investigators, said sources familiar with the probe
the sources outlined the memos contents following the account in the post
a 9-year-old boy flew an ultralight airplane solo for 3{ minutes sunday, giving him a chance at being recognized as the youngest pilot to make a solo flight
it was smooth throughout,'' tony aliengena said after piloting a quicksilver gt ultralight in calm, sunny weather at oceanside municipal airport, while his parents watched
ultralights, descended from motorized hang-gliders, are not regulated by the federal aviation administration, which requires pilots to be 16 years old before they can fly solo
tony, of san juan capistrano, took off and made a touch-and-go landing on the runway, then climbed more than 100 feet before returning for a landing, said don taylor, who observed the flight as a representative of the national aeronautics association
taylor said he couldn't say exactly how the flight might be classified by the naa, which certifies aviation records
i don't know, to be honest with you,'' taylor said, noting that typical categories for ultralight records are in terms of speed, distance and time
the naa might create a new category or just ``recognize'' the flight, he said
according to the guinness book of world records, the youngest previous solo pilot was cody a. locke, who flew a cessna 150 near mexicali, mexico, on feb. 24, 1983, at the age of 9 years, 316 days
on sunday, tony was 9 years and 295 days old
tony became interested in flying because he has flown as a passenger in a plane owned by his father, gary aliengena, since the age of 3. when he was 7, tony was allowed to sit at the plane's dual controls and guide the craft with his father
on march 30, tony and an instructor plan to take off in a cessna 210 in an attempt to to break the record for the youngest pilot to fly across the united states. missile, denies shelling iraqi cities, background on missiles. pick up 10th graf pvs: the iraqi news agency...</note>
iraq said it fired a missile into tehran sunday to retaliate for iranian artillery attacks that killed 21 people in iraqi border towns
iran vowed revenge, indicating a resumption of the ``war of the cities'' after an uneasy two-day truce. a 12-day missile duel on each other's capitals killed scores of civilians
if the iranian regime continues its aggression, then our retaliation will continue with all-out strength,'' an iraqi military spokesman was quoted as saying by the iraqi news agency
iran's islamic republic news agency (irna), monitored in cyprus, confirmed that tehran was hit. it said the missile exploded in a residential neighborhood killing and wounding ``a number of civilians.'' the agency gave no figures
irna quoted an official spokesman as saying, ``iran's moslem combatants will severely retaliate'' and he warned baghdad residents to evacuate the iraqi capital. the spokesman, who was not identified, also denied as ``pure fabrications'' the iraqi claim that iran had shelled iraqi border towns
an iraqi military spokesman, speaking on television, said iran broke the conditions of the city-war truce by shelling civilian areas. he also said iranian forces launched a ground attack in the central sector of the front
iraq will retaliate on tehran for one time, as a warning to the iranian regime,'' said the spokesman, who was not identified
the iraqis said a single al hussein missile, which has a range of 400 miles, was fired at tehran 290 miles from the border
the iraqi military spokesman said 13 civilians were killed and 70 wounded in iranian shelling of the town of halabja, about 130 miles northeast of baghdad. another eight were killed and nine wounded in other border towns, a communique said
iraq has said it fired 71 al hussein missiles in the 12-day war of the cities, including 59 at tehran. iran fired 27 at baghdad. iran reported nearly 200 civilians killed and hundreds wounded, while iraq reported many civilian casualties but gave no figures
the al hussein missile is named after a shiite moslem saint. iraq says the missile is manufactured in iraq, but western military analysts in cyprus said it could be a soviet-made scud-b with strap-on boosters to reach tehran
iran has used unmodified scud-b missiles, which have a range of 190 miles, to attack baghdad, 85 miles east of the border
the iraqi news agency said more than 1,000 iranians were killed in the 3{-hour ground battle in the central sector of the war front. the battle began late saturday and ended early sunday
iran did not comment on the report, but the iran news agency reported that in a separate raid farther north, iranian revolutionary guards and anti-government kurdish guerrillas killed or wounded 450 iraqis
it said the combined forces seized 15 square miles of iraqi land and 12 ``strategic heights'' in the sulaymaniyah area 160 miles north of baghdad
iraq said iranian troops in the central sector were backed by tanks and artillery
infantry units of iraq's 2nd army corps repulsed the thrust, exterminating the bulk of the force,'' the iraqi agency quoted an unidentified spokesman as saying
it did not say where exactly the battle took place, but the relatively small scale of the fighting indicated it was not the beginning of iran's long-awaited major offensive
iran's last thrust, in january 1987, brought its troops to within six miles of basra. but western military analysts say iran has had difficulties mobilizing forces for a new attack
iraqi news agency quoted a military spokesman as saying iraqi planes ``dealt an accurate and effective blow to a very large maritime target,'' a reference to a supertanker, off iran during the night
it did not give the exact time of the raid. it was the fourth such claim in five days
iraq had reported ships attacks on friday and saturday, but the last confirmed raid was on wednesday when iraqi warplanes hit the maltese-flag, 41,195-ton tanker tenacity
before the attack wednesday, the ``tanker war'' had been dormant as the two belligerents hammered each other's capitals and major cities in a resurgence of the ``war of the cities.''
scores of civilians were killed in both countries in the unprecedented missile duels, which began feb. 29. iraq fired a total of 71 missiles at tehran, the holy city of qom and central isfahan, while iran shot 29 missiles. policy</head>
more than 3,000 people carrying palestinian flags and chanting slogans marched to the white house on sunday to protest israeli policies in the occupied west bank and gaza strip
many of the protesters carried signs saying, ``israelis: stop killing babies'' and ``palestinians deserve statehood.''
they condemned u.s. policy toward israel, chanting, ``reagan, shultz, you will see _ palestine will be free.''
the demonstrators called on the white house to freeze u.s. aid to israel until the israeli government supports and participates in the peace process
they also asked for a moratorium on miliary aid to israel until there is a political settlement and urged the reagan administration to establish direct contact with the palestine liberation organization
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who strongly opposes a u.s. peace plan for the middle east, is due to arrive in washington on monday for talks with president reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz
meanwhile, about 300 pro-israel demonstrators rallied near the offices of abc news to protest the network's coverage of the clashes between israeli soldiers and arabs in the occupied territories
american viewers expect the whole story, not half-truths,'' moshe roumani, a professor at the university of maryland, told the crowd gathered about a half block from the abc offices. the demonstrators later marched past the network's entrance before returning to their makeshift podium
protesters carried banners saying, ``half the truth equals a whole lie,'' ``abc _ arab propaganda network,'' and ``peter jennings _ plos man on tv.'' many in the crowd wore yellow pieces of cloth to signify yellow journalism
a spokesman from abc news was not immediately available for comment
speakers urged the crowd to write or call the network to protest the coverage, while organizers sought signatures on petitions calling upon the media ``to report the entire story.''
we believe abc news, along with the other major media, has been presenting a significant amount of news from the middle east in a manner that is biased against israel,'' the petition said
the group planned to deliver the petitions to the news divisions of abc, cbs, nbc, cable news network, mutual broadcasting system, national public radio and the public broadcasting system, and the managing editors of the associated press, the new york times, reuters, united press international and the washington post
gov. michael s. dukakis' proposal to provide health insurance to every massachusetts resident by 1992 was endorsed by a key senate committee sunday after it stripped the bill of an exemption for small employers
a final version of the bill, which dukakis has championed in his democratic presidential campaign as a model for the nation, could be on the governor's desk by the end of the month, said sen. patricia mcgovern, chairwoman of the senate ways and means committee
we are now three-quarters of the way toward having solved what is really a 40-year fight in this country to come up with a degree of coverage in health care that some of the other industrial countries have had for a long period of time,'' sen. john olver told panel members
the committee adopted the bill 7-2, sending it to the full senate
hale champion, the governor's chief of staff, said the administration was pleased with the committee vote and was optimistic that the legislature would produce a final bill the governor can support
mcgovern, the proposal's earliest advocate, said she hoped the senate could begin debate monday, so the bill could be passed and sent to a house-senate conference committee to work out differences
there are an estimated 600,000 uninsured residents in the state. it is expected that employers will pick up the tab for many of them through a series of tax breaks and pooled insurance proposals outlined in the bill
the house version pegged the state's cost over the four-year life of the bill at around $1 billion. the senate version estimates the state's share at about half that
about 90 percent of the senate version agrees with the measure passed overwhelmingly by the house two weeks ago, mcgovern said
the two versions differ mainly over a house amendment to exempt businesses of nine or fewer full-time employees from having to pay a unemployment surcharge tax if they refuse to insure their workers by 1992
the surcharge is intended to help pay for health care coverage for the uninsured. the house-backed exemption of small employers, which does not exist in the senate version, would affect an estimated 86,000 employers
the drop in gasoline retail prices has slowed and may end as early as next month, an oil industry analyst said sunday
the latest nationwide lundberg survey found pump prices dropped .37 of a cent between feb. 19 and mar. 11 to an average of 95.75 cents per gallon for all grades and services, including taxes
that was a slower rate of decline than in previous weeks and the smallest drop since last november, analyst trilby lundberg said
this drop was barely over one-third of a cent, and several indicators point to rising prices during the next few weeks if crude (oil) prices hold,'' she said
other factors contributing to a possible increase include refiners' need for profits, reduced profit margins for dealers and seasonal increases in consumption beginning in the spring and peaking in the summer, she said
according to the latest survey, prices at self-service stations were 86.39 cents per gallon for regular unleaded, 101.53 cents for premium unleaded, and 82.94 cents for regular leaded. self-service accounts for 80 percent of all sales, ms. lundberg said
full-service prices were: 116.98 cents per gallon for regular unleaded, 127.27 cents for premium unleaded, and 112.75 cents for regular leaded
prince edward, the youngest son of queen elizabeth ii, denied on sunday a british newspaper report that he plans to marry the roman catholic daughter of a belgian baroness
the people, a weekly london tabloid, reported earlier sunday that the 24-year-old prince had proposed to georgia may, 22, whose mother, catherine, was born a baroness in the van den branden de reeth family
it's all complete fabrication,'' edward said when he arrived at the british academy of film and television arts craft awards ceremony in liverpool
the people report noted edward would have to give up his right as fifth in line to the british throne if he married a catholic
britain's 1701 act of settlement states only a protestant can become the monarch.s
the newspaper quoted miss may's former boyfriend, new zealand yachtsman ed danby, as saying she told him of the engagement plan to the prince in a telephone call last week
a roman catholic church leader on sunday condemned the use of car bombs, saying the terrorist tactic could turn this central american nation into another lebanon
monsignor gregorio rosa chavez, the auxiliary bishop of san salvador, referred to the explosions friday night of two car bombs in san salvador that wounded two people
leftist guerrillas claimed responsibility for the attacks
unfortunately, this was not just one more violent episode, but an extremely grave step on the part of terrorism,'' he said in his homily at the metropolitan cathedral
speaking with journalists after the mass, he said of the car bombs: ``what we're seeing is a qualitative leap in terms of terrorist tactics, and this is extremely dangerous.''
