human rights groups say an estimated 65,000 people have been killed in el salvador's 8-year-old war between government forces and leftist rebels, with at least half of the victims civilians. mushers leave kaltag; add that finishers must arrive in nome with at least five dogs, status of non-alaskan americans in race. no pickup.</note>
the 70-year-old founder of the iditarod trail sled dog race streteched his lead sunday as front-runners and their dog teams passed the last checkpoint on the yukon river section of the race
joe redington pulled out of kaltag, on the yukon river, at 4:22 a.m. and turned toward unalakleet, 90 miles away on the wind-swept norton sound coast
redington had left only nine of the 15 dogs with which he began. race rules require mushers to arrive in nome with at least five dogs in harness
leaving kaltag 2{ hours after redington was martin buser of big lake, who had passed redington early saturday before falling back into second place again sunday. buser still had 13 dogs in harness, one fewer than saturday
buser had arrived in kaltag only 23 minutes behind redington. the town is 798 miles from anchorage, where the 1,100-mile race began march 5
defending champion susan butcher, who won the last two races in record times, left at the tiny village at 8:18 a.m., and four-time champion rick swenson at 9:58 a.m., both with 12 dogs
the next checkpoint is unalakleet, about 90 miles away on the coast of norton sound. from unalakleet, the teams run north along the coast, open to the region's sudden storms and raking winds
the first musher to reach nome will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers will split the rest. three of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out, including one saturday
redington, who founded the race in 1973, has never won, although he has competed in all but two iditarods
redington had paced the race for more than 400 miles, before buser pulled out of galena an hour ahead of him saturday. buser also arrived first at the nulato checkpoint, but then warm weather forced both men to wait until dark before setting out for kaltag
american mushers from outside alaska were paced by robin jacobson of minnetonka, minn., in 13th place. john patten of grand marais, minn., was 24th; frank teasley, jackson, wyo., 27th; terry adkins, mikado, mich., 31st; dan mceachen, snowmass village, colo., 34th; and stan ferguson, philadelphia, 45th. miles of tunnel, subs grafs 1-3 with three grafs. pick up 4th graf: excavation techniques... deletes 15th graf bgng: trains will be able... which moved up.</note>
passengers packed into trains and traveled under ground and sea to the island of hokkaido on sunday as the world's longest undersea tunnel opened to rail service
some riders had waited in line more than a week to ensure a seat on the first train that took them on the 99-mile trip from aomori at the tip of japan's largest island, honshu, to hakodate in hokkaido, the country's northernmost main island
the seikan tunnel is 33.4 miles long and 14.4 miles is under water. the aomori-hakodate trip takes about two hours, with 30 minutes inside the tunnel
excavation techniques developed by japanese civil engineers for the tunnel are to be used in the construction of the planned dover strait tunnel between england and france
transport minister shintaro ishihara, guest of honor on sunday's first hakodate-bound train, told japanese reporters after crossing through the tunnel: ``it is a technological feat without parallel in the world. it is a myth come true.''
next month, with the official opening of the seto ohashi bridge, a series of 11 spans totaling 7.6 miles linking honshu with the island of shikoku, transport officials will complete a decades-old plan of linking all four of japan's main islands by rail
but the cost of the seikan tunnel, which took 24 years to build, has fueled debate in japan in an era of declining rail service
overall construction and personnel outlays cost taxpayers about $8.5 billion at current exchange rates, well above the original forecast of $1.54 billion. the project also claimed the lives of 34 workers and ran 10 years behind schedule due to technical delays and four major floods
yukinari shojiguchi of the hokkaido japan railway co., which will lease the tunnel from the japanese railway construction public corp., said the new undersea rail line will operate at a loss
but it's worth it because more people will be coming through to hokkaido and utilizing the region, which has long been cut off from developments on the mainland,'' he said
figures released by hokkaido japan railway indicate that about 2.3 million passengers and 5 million tons of cargo are likely to pass through the tunnel each year
shojiguchi said a final estimate of operating costs still was being prepared, but did not deny reports pegging the annual level at $23.1 million
an 80-year-old ferry boat service between aomori and hakodate halted operation on the eve of the tunnel's opening. thousands of ferry fans visited the region for one last four-hour crossing over the churning tsugaru strait, site of a ferry accident that killed more than 1,100 passengers in 1954
a lot of people are sorry to see the ferries go. i don't think many will be interested in riding through a dark tunnel,'' said etsuhiro tomokane, a university senior from osaka touring hokkaido during a school break
but japanese critics charge that government officials erred in approving construction of the tunnel because of the low volume of traffic across the strait, and are skeptical of claims that the tunnel will spur regional development
as far as the current railway service goes, it's not likely that the new tunnel will help develop the region by attracting new companies,'' said scott foster, transportation analyst with merrill lynch in tokyo
while a possible extension of the ``bullet train'' high-speed line up through the tunnel could bring a turnabout, some critics say the huge additional cost of building the line, which uses different tracks, would only increase the deficits
masao takada, who operates a souvenir shop in aomori, says merchants on both sides of the tunnel are worried that it will hurt business
surveys show that the number of customers in aomori and hakodate will decline because train passengers on their way to sapporo (in hokkaido) from tokyo are less likely to disembark and shop around,'' he said
sen. paul simon's home-state support appears to be slipping as the illinois primary nears and he finds himself locked in a tight race with jesse jackson, according to the results of a newspaper poll to be published monday
a chicago tribune poll of 500 democrats likely to vote in tuesday's primary shows jackson with 32 percent of the support and simon with 29 percent
but the poll, by peter d. hart and associates has an error margin of plus or minus 5 percentage points, making the race a statistical dead heat
the latest poll, taken friday and saturday, updates one done earlier last week and published in sunday's tribune. that poll, with a similar sample and error margin, showed simon holding 35 percent of the support to jackson's 30 percent
i'm not saying every poll is inaccurate,'' simon said while campaigning sunday in chicago's chinatown. ``all i'm saying is if i get my message across to the people of illinois, they're going to vote for me.''
among other democrats in the new poll, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was third with 20 percent, rep. richard gephardt of missouri had 5 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore had 4 percent
the tribune said 9 percent of the voters were undecided and 1 percent preferred none of the candidates
the newspaper did not update its sunday poll of gop voters, which found vice presient george bush the overwhelming favorite among illinois repbulicans over rivals kansas sen. bob dole and former tv evangelist pat robertson
the new tribune poll found jackson's support strongest in chicago, which represents nearly half of the state's likely democratic primary voters. simon did best in counties closer to his southern illinois home of makanda and in the rest of cook county outside chicago
support for the two was split among racial and sexual lines. jackson was strongest among blacks and men, while simon's support was heaviest among whites and women, the poll results show
among occupations, blue-collar workers supported jackson far more than other job classifications, while simon's support was nearly even among all occupations. each networks' total awards; subs 11-15th grafs, bgng `musical variety:...', to add networks on which winning shows appeared, clarify that same director made all three commercials mentioned in commercial category. picks up 16th graf pvs, `there also...'.</note>
the last emperor'' brought bernardo bertolucci the directors guild of america's feature film award, the second jewel in what may be a triple-crown season for the italian movie director
bertolucci, who in january won a golden globe for directing ``the last emperor,'' picked up the dga award saturday night in ceremonies held jointly at the beverly hilton hotel and in new york
the dga honor boosts his odds of winning an oscar. only three times in the 40-year history of the award has it failed to coincide with the academy award direction winner
other top dga winners were will mackenzie, who received the tv comedy directing award for an episode of nbc-tv's ``family ties'' called ```a' my name is alex''; and marshall herskovitz, who won the nighttime dramatic series award for his pilot for abc-tv's ``thirtysomething.''
in all, abc shows won three of the television direction awards, cbs won two, and nbc and pbs each won one. nbc had come in first in the number of nominations with eight
bertolucci's competition was steven spielberg for ``empire of the sun,'' james l. brooks for ``broadcast news,'' lasse hallstrom for ``my life as a dog'' and adrian lyne for ``fatal attraction.''
in accepting his award, bertolucci expressed his belief that ``cinema is the most international and the most classless of expressions.''
the italian director, who won permission to film ``the last emperor'' in china's forbidden city, also observed that ``cinema is living in shyness _ i might even say fear _ of television
too many movies have been intimidated by television and have tried to imitate the rhythms and the language of television. maybe i'm an idealist, but i still think of the movie theater as a cathedral where we all go together to dream the dream together.''
other winners were:
dramatic show, daytime: victoria hochberg, ``just a regular kid: an aids story,'' abc afterschool special
musical variety: dwight hemion, ``julie andrews ... sound of christmas,'' an abc special
documentary-actuality: elena mannes, ``the kingdom divided (god and politics),'' on pbs
sports: robert a. fishman, syracuse-indiana ncaa basketball championship game, on cbs
dramatic special: judd taylor, ``foxfire,'' on cbs
commercial directorial: rick levine, for three commercials: ``trouble'' for arnott's biscuits; ``bill demby'' for dupont; and ``apt. 10-g'' for pepsi
there also were several special achievement awards
robert wise, director of ``the sound of music'' and ``west side story,'' received the d.w. griffith award, the guild's highest honor
sheldon leonard, longtime dga treasurer, was named recipient of the robert b. aldrich award for service to the guild
former guild national executive director michael franklin, who guided the organization through several important labor negotiations with producers, received an honorary life membership
the 8,500-member dga represents film and television directors as well as assistant directors and production managers in movies and associate directors and stage managers in television
four soviet army officers flew here from leningrad sunday to observe winter maneuvers by north atlantic treaty organization forces, the allied press information center reported
it said the soviets would observe the military exercises for a 48-hour period. the month-long maneuvers in northern norway involve 14,000 military personnel from eight nations
under a 1986 stockholm agreement, any country that signed the pact has the right to inspect large-scale military exercises in other countries to ensure that aggressive actions are not being prepared. the agreement also requires member states to notify the others of such maneuvers
the agreement was ratified by the united states, canada and all european countries except albania
the press center said there have been five similar observation missions. the soviets sent observers to two nato maneuvers in turkey and west germany, and east germany sent a team to west germany. the united states had observers at one exercise in the soviet union and britain one in east germany. monday. subs seven grafs for grafs 5-10 pvs: `before this ...' to update with casualty count at 91, details of shamir airport conference, confirmation of mitzna order. pickup 11th pvs: we will ... edits thruout to trim</note>
israel choked off gasoline supplies to the occupied west bank on sunday after palestinian protesters set fire to two fuel trucks and pelted others with stones. prime minister yitzhak shamir flew to washington monday to meet with u.s. officials
the army confirmed an arab died after being shot in the eye in a clash last week but denied reports that a 5-year-old boy perished from burns caused by a tear gas grenade
the army said the boy had been playing with a kerosene stove when he was fatally burned. a spokesman said the parents initially blamed soldiers but later retracted the allegation
a police spokesman said more than half of the 850 arab policemen in the occupied west bank of the jordan river and gaza strip had resigned in response to a campaign led by the palestine liberation organization
the united nations said at least 91 palestinians have been killed since anti-israeli rioting began dec. 8 in the occupied territories
sunday night, police and organizers estimated from 200,000 to 250,000 israelis gathered in tel aviv to back shamir's refusal to accept u.s. peace proposals
at the protest, demonstrators held signs that read, ``peace now, pay later,'' ``yes to peace, no to withdrawal,'' and ``america to the indians.''
the rally came one day after peace now demonstrators _ estimated by israeli newspapers at 40,000 _ protested in tel aviv, urging shamir to accept the u.s. peace plan
shamir, at an airport news conference early monday before leaving for washington, said he felt ``at peace with himself'' in his decision to reject the plan. he added he hoped his talks with president reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz would advance the peace process
after two fuel trucks were set ablaze in the west bank and others stoned, maj. gen. amram mitzna banned fuel trucks from entering the occupied west bank, the army reported
a senior official in the west bank military government said fuel would be delivered to stations that serviced hospital ambulances and certain other vehicles
we will arrange for fuel deliveries only to places where it is vital for public services,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the army confirmed economic restrictions had been imposed on the west bank town of qabatiyeh, where an alleged pro-israeli collaborator was hung from an electrical pole last month after shooting a child to death
the village will be barred from exports to jordan and will be unable to receive visitors from abroad, an army official said. qabatiyeh is also without electricity, he said
defense minister yitzhak rabin last month said israel might have to resort to economic restrictions against the 1.5 million arabs in the west bank and the gaza strip if strikes and violence persisted
police ministry spokesman nahum mendel said 450 of 850 arab police officers in the west bank and gaza had handed in their papers after underground leaflets called for their resignations
he said israeli police might be called to help
former police officers wearing civilian clothes could be seen leaving a district headquarters building in bethlehem after making their resignations official
one of them, rames, 33, who declined to give his last name, said he was influenced by last week's brutal slaying in jericho of a police officer who was accused of being a collaborator
the killing made me decide very quickly,'' he said
dozens of arab tax collectors also have resigned, and palestinians have been called on to stop paying taxes
but a senior israeli official said tax receipts were down only about 10 percent for january and february
a military court, meanwhile, indicted a soldier from the elite givati brigade for manslaughter
an army spokesman said the soldier was en route to an army base when his car was surrounded by stone-throwers. the soldier drew his weapon and shot a palestinian who cursed him, the spokesman said
israel's supreme court cleared the way for the deportation of three more palestinians after rejecting an appeal and lifting a temporary restraining order that had barred their expulsion. the three were detained before the current unrest
nine other palestinians were handed deportation orders jan. 3, and four were flown to southern lebanon on jan 12. the move drew strong international protests as a violation of geneva conventions on the treatment of civilians in occupied zones
the divided cabinet debated the u.s. peace proposals, and shamir said the 24-member body would vote on the plan after he returns from his eight-day u.s. visit
shamir has rejected several key elements of the u.s. plan, especially its call for an international conference. but he apparently held out hope of getting american agreement for changes. the plan also calls for palestinian self-rule in the occupied lands
shamir told israel radio that he would propose revisions to the plan
forming the world's longest conga line with almost 120,000 dancers was no problem sunday for members of the crowd that filled the streets of little havana for the calle ocho festival
it's very easy: just face toward downtown, grab the shoulders of the person in front of you _ and dance,'' juan carlos sanchez, organizer of the event
anna nicholas, a representative of the guinness book of world records, confirmed a record had been set at 119,986 dancers, shattering the old mark of a 10,442-person chain formed last august in canada
there's no way it could fail. as soon as the music plays, we just grab on to somebody and hang on,'' said nuvia valdez, one of about 1.5 million who turned out for the food and fun of what is billed as the nation's largest hispanic festival
the river of people along 23 blocks of eighth street _ calle ocho in spanish _ began to move when gloria estefan and the miami sound machine blared their hit ``conga'' from loudspeakers
on the street, 96 volunteers with bullhorns attempted to direct the traffic of dancing feet, while ms. estefan shouted to the crowd: ``is everybody ready? let's conga!'' a special computer program helped count the dancers, and 30 observation posts were set up
since the street was clogged, forming a single line was difficult, and untold thousands of people formed in a bevy of smaller lines in addition to the mega-line that made the guinness tally
i've never seen this many people in one place in my life,'' said jean-louis levasseur, who was vacationing from new brunswick, canada. ``there's more people on this one street than in all of the maritime provinces.''
hundreds of thousands of low-income people who are elderly or disabled may have to pay an average of $50 to $75 a month more for nursing home care under a new rule issued by the reagan administration, a published report said
the government said the rule, which takes effect april 8, would enable states to ``shift more of the financial responsibility for the cost of nursing home care to the recipient,'' the new york times reported in sunday editions
the department of health and human services said the new rule will save the federal government and the states from $160 million to $615 millon over three years, according to the newspaper
the change could affect 20 percent to 50 percent of medicaid recipients in nursing homes or other institutions, the department said
under the new rule, states will be allowed for the first time to eliminate or curtail the deductions they must now permit medicaid recipients for medical costs not covered by the state medicaid plan _ such as eyeglasses, hearing aids, dentures, physical therapy and prescription drugs, according to the times report
medicaid recipients currently deduct these medical expenses from their income before determining how much they must pay for nursing home care
the health and human services department estimated the rule will require additional payments averaging $50 to $75 a month by each medicaid recipient in a nursing home who has income from a pension, social security or other sources, according to the times
in a statement published in the federal register, the administration said the purpose of the rule was to ``reduce administrative problems for states'' and to give them ``maximum flexibility in operating their medicaid program costs,'' the newspaper said
toby s. edelman, who represents nursing home residents as a lawyer with the national senior citizens law center, told the newspaper: ``the new regulation reverses a longstanding policy of the department of health and human services. there was no congressional action or judicial mandate calling for such a reversal.''
congress could pass legislation to override the rule change, but has apparently not focused on the issue, the times said. shamir and peres. pick up 6th graf pvs: sunday night,... adds byline. edits thruout to trim and conform.</note>
prime minister yitzhak shamir left for washington early monday, saying he felt ``at peace with myself'' as he prepared to tell president reagan he opposes a u.s. peace plan
but shamir, who leaves behind a deeply divided coalition government, expressed hope for results in the peace process from his talks with reagan and secretary of state george p. shultz
the state of israel was and is always ready to stretch its hand and to participate in negotiations on establishing peace in our area. no other people desires peace like us,'' shamir said at an airport news conference
i am at peace with myself. i know i will be able to convince my interlocutors and then all the others will say: `amen.'''
foreign minister shimon peres, head of the labor party, supports the peace proposal worked out by shultz during a middle east tour earlier this month
leave in peace and come back with peace,'' peres told shamir at the departure ceremony at the ben gurion international airport
shamir, leader of the right-wing likud bloc, discussed the plan with cabinet ministers for the third time sunday but said he would not call for a government vote until after his trip
after i come back with a summation of my talks with representatives of the american government, the cabinet will meet immediately and i think we'll have a decision on this subject,'' shamir said on israel radio. ``it's a matter of about a week.''
newspapers reported some 40,000 israelis attended a rally organized by the peace now movement in tel aviv saturday night and called for shamir to accept the u.s. proposals and to end the 20-year occupation of the west bank and gaza strip
sunday night, thousands of israelis gathered at the same square in tel aviv for a counter-rally backing shamir. police and organizers estimated some 200,000-250,000 people were at the rally
the demonstrators held signs that read, ``peace now, pay later,'' and ``yes to peace, no to withdrawal.''
a shamir deputy, david levy, told the crowd that if israel adopts the u.s. peace proposal, ``it will have to go to war in the future.''
shamir, who has said the u.s. plan is ``fraught with danger'' for israel, repeated his opposition sunday but said he would propose his own ideas for peace in the region
the u.s. proposal calls for taking two steps this year: enacting palestinian self-rule in the west bank and the gaza strip and starting talks on the final status in the territories. those negotiations would be kicked off by an international conference
for his part, shamir will suggest implementing arab self-rule in the terroritories on a step-by-step basis, holding peace talks under soviet-american auspices instead of an international peace conference and using a more flexible time schedule to start negotiations, said shamir aide yossi ahimeir
shamir is scheduled to meet with shultz monday and will meet with reagan on wednesday, officials in jerusalem said
labor party legislator and former u.n. ambassador abba eban also left for the united states on sunday, saying he hoped to make it clear to american officials that the conservative prime minister represents only half the israeli government. the other half, he said, would like to see israeli involvement in the peace plan
we can't appear as a country that refuses every chance for peace,'' labor legislator rafi edri said on the radio. ``the time has arrived for him (shamir) to return to reality.''
