panama's political turmoil has been a wrenching experience for three panamanian diplomats who are defying the sentiments of most of their washington colleagues by remaining loyal to embattled strongman manuel antonio noriega
two are described by acquaintances as showing signs of emotional stress as a result of panama's ordeal while a third has remained holed up in the country's consular affairs office since the crisis began more than two weeks ago
most panamanians attached to diplomatic offices in the united states closed ranks around ambassador juan b. sosa, who refused to recognize the february 26 change in government in panama and continues to support ousted president eric arturo delvalle
with u.s. backing, sosa has declined to relinquish control over the embassy despite efforts by the noriega-controlled government to replace him
a number of panamanian diplomats elsewhere have broken with noriega as well. the latest known case involves the consul general in atlanta, jaime trujillo, who notified sosa on thursday that to continue supporting the present leadership ``would contribute to the disintegration of the panamanian family.''
the three panamanians in washington who have stuck with noriega have close personal ties to the defense chief or his inner circle, according to friends and colleagues, all of whom insisted on anonymity
roberto leyton, who has known noriega for years, is panama's ambassador to the organization of american states and is the highest ranking of the three. leyton is described by one acquaintance as having lost weight and has been keeping an unusually low profile. he has refused to return a reporter's phone calls
his principal deputy at the oas, lawrence chewning febrega, broke with noriega a month ago after being ordered to deliver an anti-u.s. speech which he felt contained misrepresentations. he said he also was troubled by evidence of corruption in panama
it wasn't until two weeks later that panama's crisis came to a head. delvalle attempted to fire noriega but was ousted himself within hours in a noriega power play that included a late-night vote by noriega supporters in the country's congress
since then, alejandra sarmiento, a consular affairs officer, has remained confined in the building where she works adjacent to the panamanian embassy
according to acquaintances, ms. sarmiento is worried that if she departs the office, she will not be allowed to return. sosa has taken no action to evict her
ms. sarmiento is said to be a friend of nander pitty, a former oas ambassador who is now a top aide to noriega
the military attache at the embassy is capt. jose motta, the only embassy official who reports to noriega and not to the ambassador
as a professional soldier, motta is not called on to make political judgments and believes that his role is not affected by political shifts back home
but a panamanian diplomat who has been in contact with motta said the captain has been under a doctor's care recently for high blood pressure, a condition which worsened after the crisis erupted
his appearances at the embassy have been more infrequent lately, and he often stays only for a few minutes before departing. the relationship between motta and others at the embassy is said to have become strained
