weary firefighters worked sunday to extinguish hot spots still smoldering in a brush fire that charred hundreds of square miles of texas prairie
state and federal officials began a damage assessment, and gov. bill clements' office was considering whether to issue a disaster proclamation early this week
the blaze, which started thursday as a trash fire, burned about 300,000 acres in one county alone, raced into sections of four other counties and threatened the towns of albany and moran in shackelford county and baird in northern callahan county, just east of abilene in the north-central part of the state
but hundreds of volunteer firefighters and three tanker airplanes dropping fire-retardant chemicals contained the brush fire saturday
the fire killed livestock, burned trailer homes and oilfield equipment and closed roads
about 80 people who fled their homes opted to remain sunday night in a shelter set up in a church across from the albany city hall, said jerri malone, a spokeswoman for the red cross in abilene
bill terry, also with the forest service, noted that the fire consumed from one-third to one-half of grassland in shackelford county
the fire is still smoldering in some places but it's a case of flareups within burned areas. there has been no movement in the fire line since yesterday,'' tom millwee of the state division of emergency management said sunday
the head fire has been in essence stopped. at one time, we talked about it being a 60-mile-long stretch from interstate 20 by baird and north to albany,'' he said
the charred area stretched about 60 miles long and 25 miles wide in parts of callahan, shackelford and throckmorton counties
representatives of the department of public safety, texas forest service and federal agencies met sunday to decide whether to declare the fire under control, but put off the decision
the forward advance has been halted,'' said pat ebarb, head of the fire control department for texas forest service in lufkin. ``now, what we have to do is make sure the fire that's bumping up against our control lines is extinguished.''
many of these big fires have a history of laying there and then coming back out. we don't want that to happen this time,'' he said
once the mop-up begins, ``that'll take about two days,'' said sam logan, public information officer for the texas forest service. ``we'll continue to keep an eye on it, because with the strong winds and low humidity, just a spark could start it up all over again.''
we've pretty well got fire guards around the complete fire,'' said pat mckennon, the baird fire chief. ``we will have forest service crews out and some local fire units out, just more or less patrolling.''
state forest service spokesman joe fox said about 70 percent of the total damage was believed to have occurred in shackelford county, where the flames covered about 300,000 acres of rangeland, or a little more than half of the county's 915 square miles
the federal emergency management agency in washington approved aid saturday to help reimburse the state for expenses of fighting the fire in throckmorton, jones, haskell, callahan and shackelford counties, said carl suchoki, fema spokesman in washington
it looks like the baird area is well controlled,'' said millwee. ``they had isolated fires last night _ mostly burns within the main burn _ and there was a little more of that kind of activity, hot spots to contend with, in the albany area.''
albany, the county seat of shackelford located 31 miles northeast of abilene, has about 2,500 residents. baird has about 1,700 and moran about 350
millwee said no figures on loss of livestock or crops were yet available and a monetary damage estimate had not been made
the county (agricultural) agents are working through the system, looking at any prospects for usda or other disaster declarations,'' he said
mnay firefighters suffered smoke inhalation and minor burns, said millwee, but no residents were hurt
