eddie was diagnosed as having bone cancer dec. 10, a day after his 17th birthday, mrs. mikek said. before his illness, the high school junior stayed busy helping at his parents' grocery store and working a part-time job at a hardware store
after the diagnosis, he was able to attend school several days a week between chemotherapy treatments, mrs. mikek said, but schoolwork had to stop when he came to chicago for surgery
the family had to sell the store, said mrs. mikek in a telephone interview from the ronald mcdonald house, where she stays when she is visiting eddie
on march 4, doctors at the hospital removed a bone tumor from eddie's left leg and implanted part of a femur taken from a cadaver. they also installed a mechanical knee joint. the relatively new surgical technique, called limb salvage, avoids amputation, and should allow eddie eventually to walk normally, mrs. mikek said
the nine mile 2 nuclear power plant, which began providing power on a permanent basis friday for the first time in its troubled existence, automatically shut down sunday night when a water pump malfunctioned, a plant official said
the $6.3 billion facility, described as the most expensive nuclear plant ever built in the united states, underwent what officials term an ``unusual event'' at 5:45 p.m. sunday
robert burtch, a spokesman for the niagara mohawk power corp., said the problem occurred when the plant lost its main feed water pump, which provides water pressure to the reactor
the plant was operating at 99 percent power,'' burtch said. ``but when that (the water pump) tripped, the water level in the reactor dropped and caused the plant to automatically shut down.''
burtch said the actual problem was corrected within 15 minutes and the water in the plant was quickly replenished
but any time there's an automatic activation of an emergency cooling system,'' he added, ``we have to activate the emergency plan.''
the ``unusual event'' is the lowest emergency classification that exists for nuclear plants
officials declined to speculate when the plant might return to full power
we're looking right now to determine the cause, but obviously we're not going to start back up until we know what went wrong,'' burtch said sunday night. ``we'll know more tomorrow.''
the 1,080-megawatt plant, which was supposed to have been completed in 1977 at a cost of $423 million, began providing power on a permanent basis when plant operators declared it ``on-line'' around 3 p.m. friday
