amnesty international claims that burmese government forces have arbitrarily arrested, tortured and executed hundreds of unarmed civilians since fighting against rebels intensified in 1984
the london-based organization said that its interviews with more than 70 refugees and statements from independent investigators have produced the names of more than 200 victims, most of whom belonged to minority ethnic tribes including the karens kachins, mons, kayahs and shans
in its february newsletter, the human rights organization said the victims were attacked ``apparently because of their non-violent political opinions or activities, their ethnic origins or language.''
the newsletter was available monday in bangkok
it said the burmese government has not responded to several letters in which amnesty international expressed its concern
a dozen ethnic groups have been fighting the rangoon government for decades, saying it has denied them the autonomy they were entitled to under the terms in which great britain granted independence to burma in 1948
the newsletter said most of the people it blamed for human rights violations were army troops engaged in counter-insurgency operations in zones suspected of being under rebel influence. members of the military intelligence service, the special branch and the people's police force also were implicated, it said
eyewitnesses describe numerous instances in which burmese troops shot and killed unarmed villagers on suspicion of association with the insurgent karen national union,'' the newsletter said. ``in many cases people were apparently killed on the basis of unsubstantiated allegations from informers.''
