recent political developments in panama have put japan in the awkward position of having to choose between pleasing washington or maintaining good relations with its top latin american trading partner
foreign ministry officials have withheld an official position on the government installed by military strongman gen. manual antonio noriega as tokyo apparently plays for time, hoping to avoid aggravating the united states, which regards ousted president eric arturo delvalle as panama's legitimate ruler
but japan's considerable commercial interests in panama give tokyo strong incentive to maintain good relations with noriega's government
panama is not only a major consumer of japanese goods, it also controls the panama canal, a vital link for japanese cars headed for the eastern united states and agricultural products returning to japan
on feb. 25, delvalle ordered the resignation of noriega, who is under indictment in the united states on drug trafficking charges. the next day, however, the national assembly, controlled by noriega, dismissed delvalle and appointed solis palma as president
last week, the u.s. state department asked japanese counselor for political affairs ryozo kato to explain tokyo's position on noriega's government. assistant secretary of state elliott abrams in turn explained washington's opposition to noriega
foreign ministry officials in tokyo say japan simply has not decided whether to recognize palma's government. they refused to give any indication of when such a decision will be made
rumors that tokyo had in effect recognized the new government by sending its ambassador to palma's inauguration were untrue, said one ministry official
the presense of our counselor, instead of the ambassador to panama, at palma's inaugural ceremony is a sign of uncertainty,'' said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``we have not yet decided.''
tokyo may find it difficult to distance itself from noriega, who has visited japan several times in recent years in his capacity as head of panama's armed forces
japan has a $3.2 billion trade surplus with panama, and is panama's second-largest trading partner after the united states. in turn, panama is japan's largest export market in latin america, as well as the top recipient of japanese direct investment in the region
panama absorbed $2.4 billion, or 51 percent, of japan's private direct investment in latin america in 1986 _ one-tenth of all direct investment by japanese companies. it received 41 percent of japan's $15.6 billion accumulative direct investment in the region from 1951 to 1985, according to the foreign ministry
japanese companies have financed economic development projects, medical and educational facilities in panama
a foreign ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that aside from a halt to all banking activities, which has prevented business among japanese banks operating in panama, recent political unrest has had little effect on japanese commercial activities in the nation
so far there is no cause to expect any major problems,'' she said
since banks can no longer issue letters of credit, ``in panama, everyday is sunday,'' said masaya hasebe of the japan external trade organization (jetro)
u.s. lawmakers including sen. alfonse d'amato, who favors a u.s. trade embargo against panama, have expressed concern that tokyo might follow its economic interests in recognizing palma's government
d'amato said a number of legislators hoped to see ``that the japanese do not become involved in helping to finance and prop up this dictator for their own private economic gain.''
jetro's hasebe said japan probably would ``have to cooperate'' with the united states and reject noriega's government _ a move that could have some economic costs
there are many banks and manufacturers with businesses in panama, but no factories,'' hasebe said. he said some of the japanese firms are paper companies set up as tax havens
while tokyo has given no official indication that it would recognize the government put in place by noriega, japan has a clear interest in ensuring its access to the panama canal
japanese ships accounted for 13.1 percent of the 64.5 million tons of cargo shipped through the canal from the pacific to the atlantic in the 1985 fiscal year ending in september 1986, including many of its cars destined for markets in the eastern united states
in the same period, japan accounted for 26.1 million tons, or 35.2 percent of the total 74.2 million tons shipped from atlantic to pacific
japan ships petroleum from mexico and venezuela, grain from the united states and iron ore from brazil through the canal
hasebe of jetro said there was little concern that the canal, which is jointly operated by the united states and panama, would be closed to traffic
all the government can do right now is wait and see, looking at the future of panama,'' he said
prudential insurance co. of america may be about to lose an ally in the case of the missing zeroes, a clerical error on a financial document that could cost the company tens of millions of dollars
in a case that is the talk of the town among bankruptcy lawyers, prudential is trying to establish in court that a mortgage lien it holds is for $92,885,000
the problem is that someone mistakenly left three zeroes off a form and recorded the lien's value as only $92,885 _ one-tenth of 1 percent as much
the lien is on eight huge container ships that belonged to united states lines, a giant shipping company whose assets are being sold off to satisfy creditors in u.s. bankruptcy court in manhattan
united states lines agreed in principle in january not to contest prudential's claims about the value of its lien in return for payments from prudential totaling up to $5.45 million
but with a hearing to wrap up that agreement scheduled for this wednesday before judge howard c. buschman iii, united states lines seems to be on the verge of demanding a larger payment from prudential _ and possibly challenging the lien's validity if prudential doesn't go along
because prudential holds a first preferred ship mortgage stemming from a $160 milion loan to united states lines made in 1978, it can collect all the money raised from the sale of the eight ships, up to the amount of its lien
a lawyer for united states lines last week refused to say whether the company planned to oppose prudential over the missing zeroes, but made it clear he feels the shipping company has leverage over the insurer
we believe we're on sound ground that the mortgage can be avoided for the benefit of all u.s. line's creditors,'' said alan kornberg, a lawyer for milbank tweed hadley &amp; mccloy
the sale of the first five of the lancer-class ships earlier this month brought in $44.1 million, nearly triple what was expected, and other creditors are clamoring that united states lines deserves a payment from prudential of more than $5.45 million
judy liu, an attorney for prudential's law firm, weil gotshal &amp; manges, declined to comment
lawyers in the case clearly have little sympathy for prudential's argument that the dropped zeroes amount to nothing more than a harmless mistake
the federal ship mortgage act is a notice statute that has very strict reporting requirements,'' said sandy mayerson, a lawyer at kelley drye &amp; warren representing general electric capital corp., which shares a second mortgage on the ships
my client actually lent $57 million to the debtor, so anything it does to try to obtain the repayment of that is certainly to be expected,'' she said
prudential says the lien was improperly recorded by someone at the law firm of haight, gardner, poor and havens. it says if its lien is not upheld it may file malpractice suits against haight, gardner and its overall outside counsel on the transaction, dewey, ballantine, bushby, palmer and wood
attorneys for those firms have declined comment on the malpractice matter
the head of firestone tire &amp; rubber co. says he will not meet with the chairman of italian tiremaker pirelli until firestone consults its advisers on pirelli's $1.9 billion buyout offer, according to a report published sunday
john j. nevin, firestone chairman and chief executive officer, informed pirelli chairman leopoldo pirelli by letter saturday that firestone's board needed to examine the offer more closely, the akron beacon journal reported
nevin was replying to two letters he received from pirelli last week asking for negotiations on the italian company's offer to acquire firestone for $58 a share
i appreciate the invitations to meet with you that were included in your letters,'' nevin responded
it would, however, in my opinion, be inappropriate for me to meet with you before i have had the opportunity to obtain the advice and counsel of our board and any directions or instructions that the board may deem it appropriate to give to me,'' he wrote
nevin also said firestone, with the help of outside financial and legal advisers, is compiling background information on pirelli for use in reviewing the offer
firestone has until friday to respond to pirelli's bid. firestone already has said it planned to sell 75 percent of its tire business to bridgestone corp. of japan for $1.2 billion
a shortage of japanese computer chips is rattling the domestic computer industry, with prices of some important memory chips doubling in the past year, according to a published report
the san francisco examiner reported in its sunday editions that chips selling under contract for $2.15 a year ago now are in short supply, and their prices have shot up to the $5 range. some companies are buying chips on the spot market at even higher prices to get extra supplies
the price of chips is out of hand,'' said jim cavuto, editor of an industry newsletter, micro publishing report. ``chips are the fuel of the computer industry. it keeps us running and there should be an unlimited supply.''
some industry observers trace the problem to a 1986 semiconductor trade agreement between the united states and japan. the accord set up fair market value prices for semiconductors, such as essential memory chips used in computers. it banned third-country dumping and the japanese agreed to open up their economy more to american products
but at the time, most u.s. companies had dropped out of the memory chip business completely
only two companies, texas instruments of dallas, and micron technology of boise, idaho, still make dynamic random access memory chips, or d-rams, an essential memory chip for semiconductors. japan has 90 percent of the d-ram market, according to the san jose market research company, dataquest inc
we send our procurement people to japan all the time and use every bit of leverage we can bring to bear to make sure we're getting our share,'' said john young, president of hewlett-packard co
semiconductor makers in japan deny they deliberately are short-changing u.s. customers. they say the time-consuming conversion of factories to develop d-rams instead of 256 kilobit chips and increased demand have caused the chip shortage
they (japanese suppliers) have to wait and see to avoid oversupply and charges of dumping,'' said michihiro inoue of matsushita electrical co. in osaka. ``it takes time to put a new production system into orbit.''
inoue predicted japanese companies would catch up with chip demand later this year
usx corp. chairman david roderick received a $600,000 bonus last year in addition to his $763,982 salary and other top executives also received substantial bonuses, according to the oil and steel giant's annual proxy statement
the 1987 bonuses came as usx significantly improved its financial performance, posting a profit of $219 million in 1987 after losing $1.83 billion in 1986
usx bonuses are set individually by the board of directors' six-member compensation committee, based on the total amount of incentive compensation available as determined by the entire board
roderick's bonus was his highest ever, said usx spokesman william ryder. roderick's last disclosed bonus was $275,000 in 1985
usx did not report any incentive compensation for its top executives in 1986. that means it either did not pay bonuses or awarded bonuses worth less than $25,000, which need not be disclosed, ryder said
hourly workers at usx will receive extra compensation this year under a profit-sharing plan. usx said in january it would pay about $28 million, or an average of $1,700 apiece, to its steelworkers under the plan
those payments were triggered by a formula based on the stock prices of usx's competitors
other top usx executives and their 1987 earnings include:
_charles a. corry, president of the diversified businesses and recently named president of usx, who received salary of $301,020 and a $245,000 bonus
_thomas c. graham, president of uss, usx's steelmaking division, who made salary of $478,600 and received a $275,000 bonus
_william e. swales, president of usx's marathon oil co. subsidiary, who received salary of $446,768 and a $325,000 bonus
_w. bruce thomas, chief financial officer, who received salary of $449,814 and a $275,000 bonus
federal securities laws require companies to disclose compensation for their highest-ranking officers
american standard inc. said sunday it was in discussions regarding a cash buyout of more than $75 a share, or about $2.35 billion, and its board of directors expected to consider definitive bids at a wednesday meeting
american standard also indicated it would drop its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover plan if more than 50 percent of the company's shares were bought under a formal tender offer
black &amp; decker corp., which has offered $73 per share, or about $2.27 billion in cash for american standard, has sought removal of the poison pill and demanded more financial information since launching its hostile takeover attempt in february
black &amp; decker has been provided with the same information as that provided to other potential bidders and has been invited to meet with management and submit its own bid,'' american standard said in a statement issued from its new york headquarters
black &amp; decker's lawyers were expecting the information on sunday and the company likely would have no statement before deciding whether to sweeten its outstanding offer, spokeswoman barbara lucas said
american standard rose $1 to $73.25 a share friday on the new york stock exchange. black &amp; decker dipped 25 cents to $17.37{
george mcgrath, a spokesman for american standard, said an offer of more than $75 a share would top black &amp; decker's current offer and would relegates american standard's own defensive recapitalization plan _ which would pay shareholders a package of cash and securities valued at about $71 a share _ to a back burner
mcgrath declined to give other information about third-party offers or to disclose how many bidders were involved in discussions with american standard, a plumbing and air conditioning manufacturing company
this ($75 bid) emerged from the discussions,'' he said
while noting there was no assurance the $75 bid would be accepted, american standard cited the new developments in saying it would drop its poison pill, which makes a takeover prohibitively expensive by requiring the surviving company to buy back shareholders' stock at half of market value
noboby could have done it with the poison pill,'' mrs. lucas said
american standard has fought black &amp; decker's bid for months, rejecting its overtures, developing the recapitalization plan to thwart the takeover and winning a court battle validating its poison pill
black &amp; decker, the towson, md.-based tool and appliance maker, initially offered a buyout at $65 a share, later sweetening it to $68 and finally to $73
their confidence undermined by the collapse of their favorite stocks last october, to say nothing about the destruction of pet theories, some analysts are reaching into history for guidance
and those who do so have a tendency to remain bearish
the reason for this isn't difficult to discern, because a retracing of prior declines, such as in 1929, isn't unusual for subsequent rallies. often, however, those rallies lead only to further collapses
at its post-crash high of 2,072 points a week ago, the dow jones industrial average had risen more than 320 points, or 20 percent, from its oct. 19 bottom of 1,738
the comparison with 1929 is as hard to avoid as it is painful to recall
four-and-a-half months after the debacle of october 1929 the industrial average had recovered 43 percent of its late 1929 decline, and a bit more than one month later it reached its high for 1930
but, wright investors' service reminds us, ``within seven months all of that recovery was lost, and the downward spiral which would last until july 1932 was resumed.''
while the year 1929 is imprinted on every schoolkid's mind, the further collapse from early 1930 to mid-1932 was several times larger, and at some points along the way the descent was just as precipitous
but history can also be a treacherous guide; while it teaches, it can deceive, too. the years 1929 and 1987 have certain similarities, especially in regard to economic excesses, but the differences are probably more numerous
to begin with, the economy currently shows few signs of collapse, even in spite of some enormous and unpredictable excesses in matters such as budget deficits, credit extension and trade balances
wright and others point out that today's economy is still creating jobs at a strong level, the service sector is growing, manufacturing has been gaining strength, and after years of decline the nation's exports are increasing
there are few signs of recession. the conference board economic model released today shows gross national product rising only 2.1 percent this year, compared with 2.9 percent in 1987. that's anemic to be sure, but still growth
albert t. sommers, economic adviser at the board _ an independent group supported largely by business _ says the economy has simply entered an inevitable retrenchment, ``but does not seem poised for a recession.''
in the market itself there are signs of heightened activity, especially regarding stocks of companies that are takeover targets. merger mania has gripped the marketplace once more, and some of the premiums offered for companies seem beyond reason
less obvious, however, have been areas of underpricing in the market. business week magazine calls the over-the-counter market, where many smaller companies are traded, a bargain-hunter's paradise for undervalued shares
these stocks, some of which could be tomorrow's blue chips, failed to rise to the sky during the industrial average's long ascent. moreover, they fell more sharply than blue chips during the october collapse
now, many of these stocks are selling far below their net cash value and so have begun attracting the interest of what wright suggests are rather sensible investors. it might, says john wright, be a good sign for the entire market
while conceding that such activity might not continue, it suggests to him that for the moment, at least, ``rational investors are regaining some control of the market.''
